report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  71 year old woman with recurrent syncopal spells with a dazed look, hypertension, diabetes,  obesity, obstructive sleep apnea.

MEDICATIONS:  Lisinopril, Heparin, Nifedipine, Lisinopril, Insulin, Protonix, ASA


INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic stimulation is completed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is mildly slow with a posterior dominant rhythm of approximately 7.5 Hz. The patient is quite drowsy and rapidly drifts off into a drowsy pattern over steeper stages of sleep. Photic stimulation elicits an unilateral driving response, better elicited on the left compared to the right. In addition, the photic stimulation serves to alert the patient, at which point the left hemisphere seems to generate faster frequency better than the right.

HR:	58 bpm


IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. 	Generalized background slowing and disorganization.
2. 	Disruption of faster frequency activity on the right supporting a cortical process.


CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The patient's hypersomnolence is more of a clinical issue. There are no epileptiform features noted. The focal features described above may be correlated with imaging.

HISTORY: 69 year old male with psychiatric symptoms, boarding home resident and syncope versus seizure.

MEDICATIONS: Clozapine, Metformin, Avandia, Diovan, Metformin, Amiodipine


INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab/bed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed.  This is an awake record. The EKG lead is not functioning.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates rhythmic background slowing. There is a posterior dominant rhythm of 6-7 hertz, a scant amount of arrhythmic delta activity and generous beta.


EKG: N/A.


IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1.    Rhythmic background slowing.


CLINICAL  CORRELATION: These findings are nonspecific. They may be seen in a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy, postictal status or dementia. There were no epileptiform features.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 	64 year old right handed female with bradycardia. Past medical history: Stroke, hypertension, seizures in October 2009.
MEDICATIONS: Fentanyl, Atropine, Fludrocortisone,  Calcitriol, Levetiracetam, Alendronate, Insulin, Heparin,  Lorazepam, Clonidine, ASA, Zocor
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There are episodes of shifting slowing bilaterally. First it slows on the right but later in the record she has bursts of delta on the left as well. There are first bursts of slowing theta as well as bilateral delta. The record is also
disorganized. She does reach an alpha rhythm of 9Hz but this is amidst otherwise, slow disorganized EEG.
HR:	84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Moderately abnormal EEG due to:
1. 	Shifting slowing of delta waves bilaterally.
2. 	Disorganized and slow background.
3.	No sharps or spikes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   These findings are nonspecific and can represent either stigmata of ischemic cerebrovascular disease or a toxic metabolic encephalopathy.  A
repeat EEG can be performed as warranted.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 	69 year old right handed male, admitted with psychosis and a staring spell.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Insulin, Heparin, Morphine, Clozaril, Metformin
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed  at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is intubated and poorly interactive but arouses spontaneously.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG varies from a lower voltage theta delta pattern to one with generous amounts of beta.  Shifting slowing in the temporal regions is identified.  As the patient drifts off to sleep, vertex waves and an increasing beta are noted.  Single electrode artifact is picked up at T2.
HR:   66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.  Generalized background  slowing
2.  Disorganization.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are nonspecific and support a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.  No epileptiform features were noted.   If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow-up study after the patient is out of the ICU may be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 69 year old right handed male with recurrent blinking, diabetes, and a psychiatric illness.

MEDICATIONS:  Clozaril, Haldol, Zyprexa, Insulin, Lorazepam,  Heparin, Acetazolamide, Ceftriaxone, Morphine, Dilantin, Pantoprazole

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. The patient is awake and has frequent eye blink. He is also restless.

DESCRIPTION OF 	RECORD: The background EEG varies between a moderately slow delta with smaller amounts of beta and delta pattern followed by a pattern with more alpha theta frequency activity when the patient is agitated and coughing.

HR: 	NA.


IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Moderate background slowing.


CLINICAL CORRELATION:   No epileptiform features were seen.  Previous EEG's were not available for comparison.  This slow and disorganized pattern is nonspecific and can be seen in multiple neurologic  processes including toxic or metabolic encephalopathy.

CLINICAL HISTORY.: 79 year old woman with severe coronary artery disease, COPD, stroke, breast cancer and a syncopal event with dizziness and head trauma on 12/28.

MEDICATIONS: Spiriva, Zocor, Metoprolol, Advair

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. There is no hyperventilation or photic stimulation. This is an awake and drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates relatively rhythmic background slowing with a posterior dominant rhythm of 7.5 hertz, 40 microvolts and primarily a theta or alpha theta frequency background. Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements. Heart rate irregular at 90 BPM.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is a nonspecific pattern and can be seen in a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function. No epileptiform features were observed. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing in the lab with photic stimulation and more extensive sleep may be appropriate.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 48 year old woman status post 22-minute cardiac arrest
followed by tonic-clonic seizure. Date of tonic-clonic seizure not provided.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Heparin, Lasix
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a mixed theta and alpha frequency pattern. There are some sections of the record which are better organized in which there is a greater quantity of 9-10 Hz alpha activity, but other sections of the record demonstrate more significant theta. There is also an intermittent asymmetry with at times a bit slower theta on the left compared to the right as well as disruption of faster frequency activity on the left compared to the right. This can be seen in the frontocentral regions. Drowsiness is characterized by a transition more toward the theta delta pattern from the alpha theta pattern.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Intermittent shifting asymmetries with a tendency to have a bit more focal slowing on the left compared to the right. ╖
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are nonspecific but support a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function. In the context of a cardiac arrest, the findings are relatively modest.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 67 year old right-handed man with a syncopal event.
MEDICATIONS: Lipitor, Hydrochlorothiazide, Zelia (?), Cozaar. Metoprolol
IMPRESSION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic simulation was
performed. This is an awake through stage II sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 8.5 Hz alpha rhythm.
There i s occasional right or left temporal theta but more so on the left. The temporal
theta on the left is at times sharply contoured. Vertex waves are seen in stage I sleep
with spindles in stage II. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to: .
1. . Occasional temporal focal slowing with theta/delta left greater than right greater
than anticipated for age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are nonspecific and can be seen in
underlying cerebrovascular disease. No epileptiform features were observed. If
epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat study capturing either the patient's
clinical events or additional sleep can be useful.

CLINICAL HISTORY: A 56-year-old male with epilepsy following cerebral thrombosis in childhood. Seizure free for the last 7 years. History of a skull defect.

MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Neurontin, Pravachol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background includes a 10-Hz posterior dominant rhythm. There is continuous skull defect at C3-T3 with higher amplitude activity in that region. Underlying this there is also a subtle disruption of faster frequency activity and some rhythmic focal slowing which is sharply contoured. There is also a subtle amount of slowing in the right.
Hyperventilation produces an accentuation of the rhythmic slowing in the left temporal region as well as bursts of rhythmic generalized slowing. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background slowing. In drowsiness the focal slowing is more prominent in the left midtemporal region.
Photic stimulation elicits driving which is best identified on the right but is relatively
subtle.
Heart rate 72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Focal slowing from the left.
2. Breech rhythm, an anticipated finding following the focal slowing.
3. Sharp waves in the region with the craniotomy, most of which are left temporal, a
few of which are left frontocentral.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 36 year old right handed woman with a stroke in 2009, rightsided weakness, myoclonic seizures. Last seizure was yesterday.

MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 to 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of background beta. In relaxed wakefulness there is a bit more theta than anticipated. Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic central theta. Stage 2 sleep includes vertex waves and spindles followed by arousals. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Very mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Mild background disorganization with an alpha rhythm that is a bit more variable than traditionally accepted.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed. No myoclonus occurred, and there were no significant focal features. In this individual with a stroke and myoclonus, an ambulatory study capturing her symptoms might be useful.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 47 year old right handed male with hepatitis C, liver transplant. Now with altered mental status and lethargy.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Oxycodone, Cipro, Oxycontin, Lasix, Spironolactone, Prednisone
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Patient is intubated and poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a continuous pattern of mixed rhythmic theta and delta with a pattern of 2 to6 Hz activity. Much of the activity is rhythmic theta. Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in muscle and a scant increase in alpha frequency activity.
HR: 104 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to
1. Generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The rhythmic background slowing is nonspecific and can be seen in diffuse disturbance of cerebral function including toxic or metabolic encephalopathy. No epileptiform features were observed. These findings may be compared to previous studies.

CLINICAL HISTORY: A 72-year-old woman admitted on the 5th or the 9th with left MCA infarct. The patient began to have recurrent complex partial seizures on the night of the 11th which recurred.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, ASA, Plavix, Lasix, Benadryl, Dilaudid
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. This EEG is recorded at multiple sections.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: EEG characteristics of the seizures include rhythmic, repetitive, theta frequency, activity primarily from the left hemisphere including left frontotemporal. Some of this also involved delta. Most seizures seem to be about 2 minutes in duration and demonstrate frequent evolution. There is little in the way of postictal confusion, and the postictal background is actually quite symmetric with a definable posterior dominant rhythm. The degree of focal slowing in the left hemisphere is quite variable. Photic stimulation does not activate the record. During the later portions of the record, because the patient is having recurrent seizures, the technologist switches over the electrodes to collodion one-by-one during the continuous record. The seizures are characterized by head turning and confusion. The patient is aphasic but she is communicative before and after the seizures, and even during the seizures she seems to be making an attempt to communicate. Clinical features of the seizures include tremulousness of the hand. The right hand comes up to the mouth. She seems more confused.
HR: 96 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Recurrent complex partial seizures.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Although the patient's mental status does return to normal, the presence of repetitive seizures meets the diagnostic criteria for status epilepticus. The patients LTM was reviewed up to 17:00 hours. By the time she got over to long-term monitoring, the seizures seemed to were slowing and the focal slowing on the left seemed to be improving.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, ASA, Plavix, Lasix, Benadryl, Dilaudid

CLINICAL HISTORY: 47 year old right handed male with metabolic encephalopathy, seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Keppra, Prednisone, Oxycontin, Lasix
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Patient is poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a mixed frequency pattern with intermittent bursts of beta but prominent delta and theta. There are shifting asymmetries noted. There are also shifting beta asymmetries but a suggestion of intermittent, sharply contoured slowing identified independently in the right or left frontocentral region. There is a bit more focality in the right hemisphere than the left. Stimulation of the patient produces muscle.
HR: 96 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Marked background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to a previous study last week, technically, this is a better quality study. While the pattern remains abnormal, from a perspective of pathology, both patterns are different but similar in terms of prognosis in that both suggest a relatively significant disturbance of cerebral function. The shifting asymmetries described above may be correlated with imaging.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 74 year old woman with acute hyponatremia and a total of 5 tonic-clonic seizures on the 18th.
MEDICATIONS: Azithromycin, Levothyroxine, Premarin, Levaquin, Lovenox, Pantoprazole, Flagyl
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is intermittent, generalized slowing and occasional left temporal focal slowing. The alpha rhythm reaches 10Hz but at times is somewhat slower. Features of drowsiness include vertex waves and spindles.
HR: 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Intermittent generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. These findings may be correlated with imaging but in an adult of this age can be seen in underlying cerebrovascular disease.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year old male with a recent head trauma with right parietal hemorrhagic contusion and a tonic clonic seizure at work. History of hepatitis C, head trauma and alcohol abuse.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Keppra, Ativan, Famotidine, Tylenol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. The patient is somewhat agitated.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG includes generous beta activity bilaterally. In addition, there is a breech rhythm Identified on the right with frequent sharp waves identified maximum T2 and F8, but sometimes with a poly spike component and with a generous field of spread into the right central and posterior temporal regions. The sharp waves persist into stage II sleep. Spontaneous arousal in and out of stage II sleep are noted. At times, the sharp waves occur in brief trains, but no sustained bursts.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Frequent right temporal sharp waves.
2. Right temporal focal slowing.
3. Excess beta.
4. Generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings support a localization related mechanism for epilepsy. A follow up study may be of use.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 70 year old woman status post code with new onset seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Insulin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 of EKG. The patient is intubated and poorly responsive. Hyperventilation and are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background and EEG demonstrates a low voltage, continuous pattern with a mixture of rhythmic and delta. There is a small amount of faster frequency activity particular1y theta in the temporal regions. Stimulation of the patient produces an in theta.
HR: 106 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Significant background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed. To place this record in the appropriate clinical context, it is to know the date of this patient CNS insult. (Code)

CLINICAL HISTORY: 75 year old woman with basilar aneurysm, multiple infarcts,
visual impairment, episode of twitching with roaming at the mouth on Saturday.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Lovenox, Protonix, ASA
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20
system or electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is quite somnolent
initially but awake at the close of the record. Hyperventilation and photic simulation -are
performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, the background includes
a pattern rich in beta frequency activity. As she becomes slightly drowsy, more
prominent background slowing is noted with shifting slowing, more significant arrhythmic
delta activity on the right compared to the left. Temporal wicket is observed. Vertex
waves are noted in sleep. Beta asymmetries are noted in sleep.
HR: 60bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
I. Prominent shifting slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The focal features may be correlated with imaging. There
were no definitive epileptiform features.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 62 year old woman with renal failure, two tonic-clonic seizures followed
by intubation, now complaining of total body pain and lower extremity swelling and erythema.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is awake but uncomfortable. Hyperventilation and photic simulation were performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is diffusely slow with a rhythmic theta  frequency pattern. There are bursts of bilateral, frontally predominant rhythmic delta. In addition, there are bursts of high amplitude delta activity in the right hemisphere with a generous field of spread. Some of these are associated with sharp waves in the right hemisphere including right central and parietal regions. Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in theta frequency activity. As the recording continues sharp waves are noted with different localizations including FP2, F8 and T4. The transition to stage II sleep Is associated with vertex waves and spindles followed by arousal.

HR: 66 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing.
2. Prominent epileptiform activity in the right hemisphere with a generous field of spread.
3. FIRDA
4. High amplitude delta in the right hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are to the previous EEGs performed in July 2009. No seizures were recorded. The studies a localization related mechanism for epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 72 year old male with hepatitis-C, epilepsy, dementia, admitted with upper respiratory tract infection and recurrent complex partial seizures.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and Keppra.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient was quite grumpy. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing beings, the patient is drowsy with primarily a theta frequency background. There are bursts of frontally predominant rhythmic delta activity but there is an asymmetry with a bit more rhythmic delta from the right hemisphere compared to the left. Stimulation of the patient produces an arousal with an alpha rhythm of 9 Hz although there is asymmetry between the 2 hemispheres with the alpha rhythm.

HR: 78 bpm.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
I. Background slowing.
2. Disorganization.
3. Occasional right greater than left frontal delta.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The background slowing and disorganization Is more prominent than that seen in previous studies. Overall this is more of a bi-hemispheric process than a unilateral process. No epileptiform features were identified.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 34 year old female with refractory epilepsy, now 15 weeks
pregnant.
MEDICATIONS: Potassium; no seizures medicines reported
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is arousable. No
clinical seizures are noted. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly slow with a
mixture of rhythmic delta and theta. There is prominent shifting slowing, intermittent
muscle artifact, intermittent beta activity and some frontocentral sharp waves a bit more
prominent on the left.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Marked background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No seizures were recorded. A review of previous EEGs in
pregnancy for this patient with refractory epilepsy may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 59 year old female with epilepsy. Recent status epilepticus.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Ativan, Pantoprazole, Trileptal

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are both attempted.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background EEG is disorganized. There is a 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm but there is variability in the alpha rhythm and excess theta. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing an increase in rhythmicity. In addition, in hyperventilation there is some focal slowing identified in the right frontotemporal region with rare sharp waves. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response which is relatively symmetric but may be a bit more vigorous on the left. This is followed by some drowsiness.

HR: 96 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing and disorganization.
2. Focal slowing in the right frontotemporal region.
3. Rare right frontotemporal sharp waves.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports both a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function as well as a structural process in the right frontotemporal or frontocentral region. Correlation with imaging is suggested. If this patient is thought to be postictal, a follow-up study may be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 62 year old right handed gentleman with epilepsy, COPD, hepatitis C is evaluated for encephalopathy. History of PEG, tracheostomy, hepatitis B, hepatitis C, DVT and seizures from the left temporal region in the past.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using a standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Photic stimulation is performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG demonstrates a mixed frequency pattern with a hint of an alpha rhythm more so on the left than the right. There is intermittent attenuation of activity in the left, particularly in the temporal region. Arousals are associated with an increase in muscle artifact. Photic stimulation suggests a driving response but the patient is moving a great deal.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Superimposed left temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed in this record today. The background slowing is not significantly worse than previous studies. If epilepsy is an important consideration additional recording and testing may be of use.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 48 year old male with a 5-minute syncopal event 6 weeks ago. No other neurologic history is provided.
MEDICATIONS: Vesicare, Carbamazepine, Nifedical, Ibuprofen
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz, 50 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm. In wakefulness there are also right anterior temporal sharp waves. During the hyperventilation part of the record there is an area of initially a low voltage, slightly irregular slowing out of the right central temporal region, followed by more rhythmic activity of initially 2-3 Hz, and then higher amplitude activity of increasing
rhythmicity in hyperventilation, which is in the right central temporal region. This activity out of the right central region occurs in the context of generalized, frontally predominant rhythmic slowing. In the post hyperventilation record, there is prominent rhythmic 7 Hz activity out of the left central region and then more definitive Mu like activity which can be seen bilaterally. The activity that looks like Mu on the left Is a lower voltage from that on the right, although the frequency is identical. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta frequency activity. Photic stimulation elicits supraharmonic driving.
HR: 66 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Rare right temporal sharp waves.
2. Subtle underlying focal slowing in the right central temporal region.
3. An unusual Mu activity that is slower that it is typically expected in higher amplitude  on the right.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The sharp waves should be correlated in this patients history, but support a focal mechanism for epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 60 year old right handed woman with a posterior cerebral artery infarct 5/10/2010, now with hemorrhagic conversion of the infarct and slurred speech.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Atenolol, Verapamil, Lisinopril, Protonix, Labetalol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is somewhat drowsy. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a slow pattern with generous frontal beta more so on the left frontal region than the right and slowing particularly in the right posterior region with low to medium amplitude slow delta. With stimulation there is a theta frequency posterior dominant rhythm and a suggestion of lambda on the left not seen on the right. As the patient transitions into sleep, asymmetric vertex waves are noted, maximum on the left. Beta activity in sleep is also maximum on the left.
HR: 90 bpm and slightly irregular
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Focal features in the right hemisphere with arrhythmic delta activity and disruption of faster frequency activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are relatively classic descriptions of a focal process involving gray and white matter. No epileptiform features were seen. The generalized background slowing supports the diffuse disturbance of cerebral function that this intracerebral hemorrhage has caused.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 42 year old right handed male with diabetes, psoriasis, acute
and chronic subdural hematoma following alcohol ingestion.
MEDICATIONS: Metformin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are
performed. This an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a pattern rich
with beta frequency activity and a smaller amount of theta frequency activity. There is a
bit of rhythmic theta delta, more so on the left than the right, and accentuated by
hyperventilation. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta. Photic stimulation
elicits a driving response. Towards the close of the record, the patient drifts into stage
2 sleep and a little bit of left posterior slowing is noted.
HR: 80 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Prominent excess beta.
2. Small amount of excess theta.
3. Shifting slowing a bit more so in the left posterior quadrant.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. If epilepsy is an
important consideration, a follow up study may be useful.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 33 year old right handed male, status post resection for glioma, past history of aphasia and hematoma.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Levetiracetam

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This an awake and sleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.7 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity. A breech rhythm can be identified from the left frontal region and there is a subtle area of focal slowing with some rhythmic 3-4Hz activity in that region. Features of drowsiness include an increase in background theta. The breech rhythm is a bit more prominent in drowsiness, as is some of the rhythmic slowing. Photic stimulation elicits driving bilaterally. Again, the breech rhythm is a bit more prominent. At the close of the record the patient starts to drift off into stage 2 sleep. The field of the left frontal focal slowing actually increases a bit more posteriorly in sleep.

HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Focal slowing primarily in the left frontal region.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this EEG nor the one 6 months ago. The focal slowing and breech rhythm are anticipated findings after craniotomy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 25 year old right handed male with epilepsy, tonic clonic seizures, post-ictal incontinence.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is excessively drowsy and there is a great difficulty keeping the patient awake.

1. Abnormal background.
2. Focal epileptiform activity including frontal, temporal or occipital.
3. Excess beta.
4. Initially excess slowing.

The epileptiform activity described today has been previously noted. Of note, the temporal epileptiform activity is much more prominent. No occipital seizures were noted and the patient is not experiencing refractory headaches at this time.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 8.5 hertz alpha rhythm. There is an intermittent asymmetry noted with destruction of faster frequency activity on the right compared to the left. Hyperventilation seems to accentuate this focality particularly in the right frontocentral region.
Drowsiness also seems to accentuate the focal features. Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record.
Right frontotemporal sharp waves maximum F8 and FP2 are observed as the patient drifts off into sleep. With the use of an average reference, this activity is maximum at F8. It is so exquisitely high amplitude that it is almost negative at the midline.
The amplitude of the discharge in F8 and T2 are 80 to 103 microvolts, but it is higher amplitude particularly at F8 rather than T2.

1. Right frontotemporal sharp waves and spikes.
2. Right frontocentral and frontotemporal focal slowing accentuated by drowsiness and hyperventilation.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  58 year old left handed man with intractable epilepsy status post VNS stimulators presents for seizure classification.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Topamax, Lacosamide
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous digital video 24 hours monitoring EEG was performed at bedside for 20 hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement syndrome with additional arterial, temporal, and EKG electrodes.  Continuous seizure detection software as well as bi-detection software was utilized and supplemented by a patient-activated alarm, nursing observation, and testing.  The video/EEG files were reviewed on a daily basis.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-formed posterior dominant rhythm at 9 to 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening with a normal frontocentral beta.  All sleep stages are captured.  For the first 20 minutes, photic stimulation and hyperventilation were performed with no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Bursts of generalized spikes and waves seen at 4 to 4.5 Hz with anterior predominance and bursts of 1 to 3 seconds.  At times, the bursts seem to have a right frontal leading and at times a left frontal leading, but mainly they are symmetric.  No other focal spikes were seen.
SEIZURES:  [captured or patient event captured]:  No seizure events or patient events were captured during this first day of recording.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Bursts of generalized spikes and waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The findings in this recording are consistent with a diagnosis of idiopathic generalized epilepsy.  Although some of the bursts are asymmetric, no clear focality can be seen to suggest a primary focal lesion with secondary bilateral asynchrony.  No seizures were captured so far in the recording.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  54 year old male with a history of hepatitis C cirrhosis, IV drug abuse, hypertension, and epididymitis who presents with change in mental status, confused and lethargic.
MEDICATIONS:  Zosyn, Vancomycin, Protonix, Dopamine, Pyridoxine, Rifampin Dexamethasone, Acyclovir, Brinzolamide
REASON FOR EEG:  Rule out seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior and temporal electrodes and EKG electrodes.  The patient was obtunded during this study.  No activating procedures were performed
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG opens to a diffuse slow background with an asymmetric pattern over each hemisphere.  The left hemisphere is mainly in the theta-delta frequencies with maximum slowing seen in the left midtemporal region.  The right hemisphere reveals a low-voltage discharge with minimal normal cortical frequencies seen, mainly in the delta frequency.
No normal posterior dominant rhythm is seen and normal frontocentral beta is absent.  At times the patient coughs and the frequencies appeared to improve to a theta pattern.  No normal sleep architecture was seen, and no activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Left hemispheric slowing maximum on the midtemporal region.
Right hemispheric attenuation.
Infrequent sharply contoured C3 sharp transients, possibly asymmetric vertex.
SEIZURES  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left temporal slowing.
Right hemispheric attenuation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural dysfunction in the left hemisphere, maximum in the temporal region, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology but has a high correlation with a lesion in that region.  The right-sided attenuation may be due to cortical dysfunction sometimes seen in stroke or overlying structural lesion like a subdural hemorrhage causing decreased attenuation.  Clinical correlation was recommended.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 22-year-old female with a history of seizures after a stereotactic frontal craniotomy for a central neurocytoma and VP shunt, now with recurrent seizures, low Dilantin levels.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin 1 gram, Ativan 12 mg, as well as added Ativan afterward; later intubated and placed on propofol.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long-term EEG for 18 hours was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional EKG and anterior temporal electrodes.  The patient was comatose and unresponsive during the EEG.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffuse background which is disorganized, mainly in the delta/theta frequencies with no normal posterior dominant rhythm and no normal frontocentral beta.  No normal sleep architecture is also seen.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges seen at T4-T6 at a frequency of 2 Hz with amplitude of 20 to 75 microvolts.  These discharges are seen continuously but appear to evolve as described in the seizure paragraph.  During the recording, these PLEDs become more blunted and less frequent, but they are continuously seen.  At times during the last part of the recording, they appeared to have more anterior predominance, moving from T4 forward to the F8 region.
Diffuse slow waves seen in the recording.
SEIZURES:   Frequent seizures are seen emanating from the T6-T4 electrode which evolve from PLEDs and stop.  There is a contralateral left hemisphere artifact as well as in the video left arm trembling can be seen during these seizures.  There are multiple of these occurring at the beginning of the recording, almost continuously. However, as the over time the recording improves, the periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges become more blunted and the seizures stop.  During the rest of the EEG, the last 10 hours of the EEG, there is only intermittent muscle artifact on the left hemisphere but no clear actual seizures being seen.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Frequent seizures arising from the left posterotemporal region, which later improve, and none seen during the last 10 hours.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of localization epilepsy arising from the right posterotemporal region, with multiple seizures seen from that region.  Please note that the seizures improve and none are seen during the last 10 hours. In addition there is continuous evidence of acute focal dysfunction and irritability in the right hemisphere.  Lastly, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction which in this patient is likely due, at least in part, to medication affect.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  84 year old woman with subdural hematomas and relatively abrupt lethargy and aphasia.

There are occasional bursts of left midtemporal sharp waves which can be broadly contoured.  They may be maximal at T1, T3 or F7.  There are also substantial portions of the record without sharp waves.  Arrhythmic delta is prominent in the left frontotemporal region.
HR:    78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Focal slowing from the left temporal region.
Left anterior temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures were recorded.  This EEG supports a focal mechanism for seizures.  If there are additional concerns a follow up EEG may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  65 year old left handed woman with a history of right sided CVA coming in with a left sided weakness and evaluated for preoperative right CEA surgery.
MEDICATIONS:  Not available.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Rule out seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  Wakefulness was recorded.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm 9-10 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 50 microvolts which is reactive to eye opening. There was small amount of frontocentral beta activity seen. Sleep was not recorded during this EEG session. Photic stimulation reveals no abnormal discharges.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Continuous slow wave in right hemisphere with a maximum of slowing on F8-T4. In addition, we have focal slowing in F7-T3 intermittently. Seizures are none.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Continuous right hemisphere slowing, maximal in the anterior temporal region.
Intermittent left hemisphere slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG showed focal structural cerebral dysfunction in the right hemisphere maximal in the anterior temporal region, which is consistent with a known stroke. In addition, there is a left focal cerebral dysfunction which is not specific in regards to etiology. No seizures or epileptiform activity was recorded.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  37 year old left handed woman with epilepsy since childhood and a break-through seizure a week ago.  Past history of left-sided encephalomalacia and gliosis.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat poorly organized.  There is a scant, 10-Hz alpha rhythm.  The major abnormalities in this record include left anterotemporal sharp waves.  These can be reviewed with an average reference and may be maximum at T1, F7, or occasionally FP1.  They are accentuated by hyperventilation and drowsiness.  There is rare, hypersynchronous bilateral theta and one or two bursts of focal, right central temporal slowing. Both hyperventilation and photic stimulation seem to increase epileptiform activity.  Brief sleep is characterized by vertex waves and an increase in beta.

Prominent, left anterotemporal sharp waves and spikes noted in wakefulness and sleep.
Background slowing and disorganization.
Rare slowing on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a focal mechanism for epilepsy.  There were no previous EEGs for comparison.  Despite the patient's abnormality in the left occipital region, the epileptiform activity is in the left temporal region.

In addition to the ECS montage, the data can be reviewed using an average reference to eliminate some of the ICU background which includes substantial EKG artifact.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  55 year old female who presented to ER with sore throat felt to have epiglottitis, multiple intubation attempts failed, ended up having a PEA code with 3 rounds of epinephrine, pulse finally returned.  Circulation now about 4-6 hours later noted to have convulsive seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Versed drip, Dilantin.
REASON FOR EEG:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Long term digital video EEG was performed for 14 hours using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with a 1 channel EKG and anterior temporal electrodes.  The study was recorded while the patient was comatose.  No activity procedures were performed.  Continuous EEG monitoring was performed and reviewed using spike detection and seizure detection software as well as nursing noted events.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a low amplitude diffusely slow background with frequencies mainly in the delta range.  No normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta is seen.  No sleep architecture is seen.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized periodic epileptiform discharges (GPEDs) were seen with anterior central maximum at a frequency of 1-2 Hz.  At times this would evolve, see description of seizures below.
Generalized slow waves seen at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  There are multiple seizures occurring per hour seen at the beginning of the recording which originate from GPEDs which increase in frequency and amplitude in seconds and later are obscured by a rhythmic intermittent muscle artifact.  The longest of these last about 40 seconds and afterwards  the background returns to baseline.  These seizures appear to subside 4 hours into the recording and after 10:30 at night no more are seen.  After this time the GPEDs appear to become slightly blunted and lower in amplitude, although at times intermittently the morphology changes to more sharply contoured but never clearly evolve into seizures.  Later in the recording in the morning hours there is some intermittent diffuse muscle artifact but no underlying evolution of seizures or epileptiform activity could be clearly seen in between the bursts of muscle.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized seizures.
Diffuse slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals multiple seizures with a generalized onset and interictal evidence of diffuse brain dysfunction and irritability.  These findings are consistent with a diffuse cortical injury and with a history of hypoxic injury.  The EEG appears to improve with time and during the last 10 hours of the recording no seizures can be clearly seen.

No normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta seen.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  No activating procedures were performed.

Generalized slow waves.

1.  Generalized periodic discharges.
Diffuse slow waves.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and EKG electrodes.  The-patient was awake during the study, but restless, lethargic, and non? co	No activating procedures were performed.

TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES: Continuous movement during the recording.

ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
1. Focal slow waves seen at the left hemisphere maximal in the F7/T1, at 2-4 Hz:
seen continuously.  In this hemisphere, however, there is a mixture of faster frequencies during the record
2. Low amplitude and lack of faster frequencies over the right hemisphere.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  51 year old right handed male with tonic clonic seizures on the 13th and schizophrenia as well as MRSA infection.  He had a breach rhythm.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is in isolation.  This is an awake and sleep record in an ill-appearing, somewhat agitated patient.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is low to medium amplitude with a theta and beta pattern.  The right hemisphere demonstrates lower voltage beta.  The left hemisphere demonstrates more theta.  There is a medium amplitude, somewhat subtle, sharp wave noted in the left anterior temporal region.  It has little bit in variability, may be seen at T1, at 7 or even T3.  There is sometimes some posterior temporal spread to it.  The sharp waves may be seen with a subtle build-up of activity and at 11:48:56, while the patient is resting comfortably with no clinical signs, there is a build-up of theta with sharp activity.  The nurses are in the room and in fact, are standing in front of the patient and working with the patient.  He is interacting during this discharge and then another discharge is noted at 11:50:16.  This is followed by higher amplitude, left anterior temporal spike and slow wave complexes.  These demonstrate a P3 maximum.  A third more subtle discharge is noted at 11:56 but does not have the same build-up.  No clinical symptoms are associated with this.
HR:    78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing.
Asymmetry with lower voltage beta pattern on the right and more of a beta pattern on the left.
Prominent sharp waves in the left hemisphere with variability including mid or anterior temporal as well as some posterior temporal.
At least 3 subtle bursts of epileptiform activity with some evidence of evolution but without clinical signs or symptoms.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The bursts described above are unclear significance.  While they are worrisome in terms of prominent, irritative epileptiform pattern, they are not remarkably evolving and there were no clinical seizures noted.  This may represent an inner ictal pattern for this individual with complex partial epilepsy.  Comparison with previous EEGs may be of value

CLINICAL HISTORY:  51 year old right handed male with a history of seizures, here for long-term monitoring.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Keppra, Dilantin
REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous digital video long-term EEG for 24 hours was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  Continuous spike and seizure detection software was used to review the EEG as well as noted patient event and nurses' reports.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some movement artifact and electrode artifact throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that, at best, reaches 6 Hz, which appears to sometimes be reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontocentral beta seen .  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and some stage changes with sleep are seen.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen frequently at F7/T1 frequently.
Focal slow waves are seen at F7/T1 almost continuously throughout the recording at 2 to 4 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  Throughout the recording, there appear to be intermittent episodes where the focal sharp waves at F7/T1 become rhythmic and increase in amplitude and evolving frequency for minutes.
During the recording there does not appear to be a clear correlate to these episodes, although at times appears to be some chewing artifact.  It is likely that these are multiple electrographic seizures occurring frequently throughout the recording.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Multiple frequent left anterior temporal electrographic seizures and sharp waves.
Focal slow waves in the left anterior temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals multiple frequent electrographic seizures arising from the left anterior temporal region with additional evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction and irritability in that same region.  These findings were communicated to the team.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  62 year old right handed woman status post left parieto frontal craniotomy for meningioma repair now with episodes where her hand migrates up in the air.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Simvastatin, Atenolol, Omeprazole, Loratadine
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm identified bilaterally.  There is a breach rhythm noted in the central region, more so on the left than on the right and there is a slight degree of focal slowing in the left central temporal region.
Hyperventilation accentuates focal slowing from the left hemisphere particularly frontal central - central temporal.  Stage 2 sleep includes vertex phase K complexes and spindles.  The breach rhythm is more prominent during sleep.  There is also some more sharply quadrant slowing emerging at P3.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is drifting off to sleep and does not clearly activate the record.  In the sleep record, the area of sharply quadrant slowing can include C3 and/or P3.
HR:    78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing from the left hemisphere which may be left central parietal in sleep and a little bit more central temporal and anterior temporal in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There were no sharp waves or spikes noted, although there was some sharply contoured slowing. A 1-hour EEG was requested to try and capture one of this patient's spells, but was not performed.  A follow-up study was requested in an attempt to capture one of her episodes with the arm flutter.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 34 year old left handed male with 2 tonic clonic seizures. Past history of childhood epilepsy which he outgrew at age 15. Now with diverticulitis, awaiting colostomy.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a relatively fast alpha rhythm with alpha squeak noted with alpha rhythm transitioning to 13 Hz. In the transition in and out of sleep, there is rhythmic theta which is more prominent in the left temporal region. It has a 4 Hz component more than a 5 Hz component and then on some occasions, has a mixture of delta noted. Hyperventilation accentuates left temporal mixed beta delta with a T1 sharp wave noted infrequently during hyperventilation. This is also a finding that re-emerges in drowsiness. Photic stimulation is performed as the patient is drifting off to sleep. There is a photic driving response identified bilaterally.
HR:    84 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
TIRDA-intermittent rhythmic mixed theta delta.
Left mid to anterior temporal sharp waves elicited by hyperventilation.
Sharply contoured delta also noted in hyperventilation.
Some extension of bilateral temporal rhythmic mixed theta delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are relatively characteristic of a temporal lobe epilepsy. Correlation with imaging and clinical history is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  29 year old right handed male with myoclonic jerking of the upper extremities for the last several years now increasing and also a concussion 2 years ago. Head trauma at age 21 and seizures for a year after that. Migraine headaches, asthma and allergies.
MEDICATIONS:  Albuterol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a symmetric reactive 9 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. In relaxed wakefulness, there are bursts of frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity. Most bursts are under a second and all discharges are under 2 seconds in relaxed wakefulness. Hyperventilation clearly accentuates the frontally predominant spike and wave and poly spike and wave activity. The major of discharges are symmetric in the frontocentral region. Hyperventilation also produces an increase in burst duration with some bursts waxing and waning, but lasting up to 6 seconds in duration. In addition, there are more clearly developed frontally predominant spike and wave and even polyspike and wave complexes noted following hyperventilation.
The technologist tests the patient and does not identify clinical correlates with these bursts. There are a handful of eye movements sometimes seen around the bursts, but no definitive focal features. As the patient transitions in and out of drowsiness, the frontally predominant spike and wave discharges become higher amplitude. Sleep is not sustained. Photic stimulation also does seem to accentuate the discharges, but there are no discharges that outlast the photic stimulation.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Frontally predominant spike and wave complexes of 3.5 to 5 Hz.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No clinical seizures were recorded. These EEG characteristics are highly suggestive of a generalized or inherited mechanism for epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  56 year old right handed gentleman with epilepsy, mesiotemporal sclerosis, HIV disease, liver failure, hepatitis C, admitted with left facial twitching and rhythmic mouth movements.

There is a prominent interhemispheric asymmetry with disruption of faster frequency activity on the right, occasional periodic or sharply contoured delta, and subtle sharp waves picked up in the right temporal region, typically T2/T4.  A handful are maximum in the lateral temporal chains, but actually phase reversed at T1.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in slowing.  In sleep, the temporal sharp waves sometimes have more of a posterior temporal field.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  52 year old right handed woman with a 2-year history of epilepsy.  Last seizure August 20, 2011.  Seizures characterized by an aura of a funny taste in her mouth followed by tonic clonic seizures.  Sleepiness.  Depression.  Alcohol abuse.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates a well-organized pattern on the left with an alpha rhythm of 10 Hz.  On the right, the alpha rhythm is sometimes disrupted.  In the right posterior region, there is a mixture of 2.5 and 4 Hz beta activity.  This is most prominent on the right but is really seen throughout the right central temporal and frontotemporal regions.  Discrete sharp waves and spikes are noted in the right hemisphere.  They have some variability and may be O2 maximum, T6 maximum, or they may start at O2 and transition to T4.  They may occur as couplets.  Drowsiness seems to accentuate the epileptiform activity in the right occipital region.  Hyperventilation also seemed to accentuate both the focal slowing and sharp waves.  Other features of drowsiness include an increase in beta.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.

Focal slowing in the right hemisphere particularly posteriorly as well as central temporally.
Sharp waves in the right hemisphere with variable maximum most prominently O2 but also T6 and T4.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the fifth EEG for this individual.  Only one of them has been normal and all other EEGs demonstrate epileptiform activity in the same area.  If seizures are not controlled, additional monitoring and intervention may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  60 year old male with multiple focal seizures involving right arm with chewing movements.  Past MCA stroke, hypertension, aphasia, pacemaker.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Ativan
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient has clinical seizures characterized by facial twitching and involuntary movements of the right arm.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins the patient has been having seizures and continues to have seizures.  The overall EEG is sharply contoured, almost a chaotic pattern, and intermittently discontinuous.  Left frontal sharp waves precede the seizure and the seizure includes a mixture of frontal and left hemispheric sharp activity and fast activity.  The activity is maximum in the front, but is really seen throughout the left hemisphere in the parasagittal region.  The fast activity is prominent in the central regions.  Some of the activity spreads to the right.
By 8:15 p.m. the epileptiform activity is a bit more isolated.  At 8:00 p.m. the patient receives a Dilantin load.  He develops respiratory distress and a pleural effusion.  He is placed on a propofol drip for respiratory management. No additional clinical seizures are observed.  The EEG demonstrates a pattern with left frontal or bifrontal sharp activity or fast activity with a discontinuous background.
HR:    104 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Initially status epilepticus pattern with repetitive seizures, improving to a discontinuous pattern with the use of both Dilantin and propofol.
INTERVAL CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG remains a highly epileptiform pattern.  There are bursts of sharp waves and spikes, but no clearly evolving seizures or clinical events noted in the later sections of the record.
LONG TERM MONITORING
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous digital video EEG monitoring was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is intubated, extremely ill, but responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates a left frontal spike or a sharp wave, which is periodic, merging to nearly continuous.  It does not evolve, as would be expected with a seizure.  The remaining background is markedly slow and suppressed.
Despite the patient's arousability, with occasional spontaneous movement and reactivity to external stimuli, the background does not improve.  It is a markedly slow and suppressed pattern with a frontal PLED with a periodicity of approximately 1 to 2 per second.
HR:    100 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Markedly suppressed background.
Left frontal PLED with a generous field of spread.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures were recorded.  This EEG continues to demonstrate a marked disturbance of cerebral function.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  46 year old right handed male with refractory epilepsy, 2 seizures recently.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  There are brief sections of the record where it is reasonably well organized with a 6.8 Hz alpha rhythm of 30 mV and a theta frequency background.  More commonly, there is frontally predominant mixed theta delta.  High amplitude or medium amplitude spike and slow wave and sharp and slow wave complexes are observed with many different localizations.  The majority of these are frontal, particularly FP2, but some are FP1, others F8, F7.  Some have a more temporal spread and others are maximum in the central or central parietal regions independently on the right or the left.  The epileptiform activity is focal, but is occasional bifrontal and generalized.
Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background slowing.  The epileptiform activity may occur in pairs, but the two pairs are not always identical epileptiform discharges, although they are usually similar in terms of both occurring on the same hemisphere.  There may be a bit more focal slowing on the right as the patient transitions to sleep. Photic stimulation is remarkable for frequent epileptiform discharges with frontal delta, some of which almost has a spike and wave component on the left, but given the abundance of epileptiform activity, it is not clear that photic stimulation activated the record.
HR:    72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Multifocal epileptiform activity with prominent activity in the right frontal region.
Spike and wave activity seen with photic stimulation, perhaps more on the left.
Background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG suggests an irritative process with epileptiform activity occurring from many different loci.  No seizures were recorded.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  23 year old woman with brain tumor, craniotomy, VP shunt, admitted with recurrent status epilepticus.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is awake.  Seizures are noted during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing opens, the patient is awake.  The EEG activity from the left hemisphere is, in fact, quite normal with a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  An alpha rhythm is also identified on the right, but there is a breach rhythm, medium to higher amplitude, arrhythmic delta activity and a sharp wave which is seen out of the breach rhythm, which may be maximum at T2 or T4.  There is also some periodic slowing noted.
The patient's first seizure occurs at 10:29:21, 6 minutes into the EEG.  She starts to pick or fuss with her covers.  She looks to the left.  She is a little bit interactive with the tech and the tech asks her to count to 10, but by the time the tech is asking her to count to 10, the seizure is over.  Total seizure duration is about 20 seconds.  Characteristics of this seizure include rhythmic, repetitive right temporal theta frequency activity and some postictal slowing.  Eye movement artifact is also prominently picked up in the temporal electrodes.
At the close of the record, as the nurse is working with the patient, an additional burst of the prominent arrhythmic delta activity is noted on the right.  The patient is awake and it is not clear that this event was considered clinically significant.
HR:    120 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
A brief, well-defined seizure out of the right temporal region.
Focal slowing in the right temporal region.
Another burst with prominent periodic delta also out of the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is diagnostic of a focal mechanism for epilepsy.  Previous EEGs demonstrated T6 seizures and PLEDs.  Today's seizures are a little bit more anterior.
