INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is slow and disorganized.  The alpha rhythm is 6 Hz with some 8 Hz activity in the background.  There is a subtle asymmetry with disruption of faster frequency activity in the left frontotemporal region compared to the right. Occasional bursts of shifting slowing are noted. Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record.
HR:    102 bpm and regular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing characterized by intermittent disruption of faster frequency activity in the left frontotemporal region.
Generalized background slowing.
Underlying disorganization.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are no epileptiform features.  While the pattern described above is nonspecific, the intermittent disruption of faster frequency activity is compatible with a structural process involving cortices might be seen following stroke.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  50 year old right handed female with history of seizures since September 11, 2011 and developmental delay.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Tramadol, Loratadine, Diovan
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures, including hyperventilation and photic stimulation, were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 7 Hz which appears to be reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontal central beta.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures, including photic stimulation and hyperventilation, produce no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Mild excessive theta in wakefulness.
SEIZURES:   None
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Excessive theta in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of mild cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old right handed male status post seizures and fall.  Seizures started 2 months ago after running out of Xanax.
MEDICATIONS:  Topamax, Keppra, Lovenox, Oxycontin, Citalopram.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that best reaches 8 Hz but appears to be somewhat reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontocentral beta.  No activating procedures were performed. The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen at T4/C4 continuously throughout the recording at 2 to 4 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolt and an associated breach in that region.
Generalized slow waves at 5 to 7 Hz seen continuously throughout the recording during wakefulness.
SEIZURES:   None
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slow waves seen at T4/C4.
Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right centrotemporal region which is consistent with the known craniotomy.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  43 year old right handed male with recent massive right MCA infarct, morbid obesity, transferred back to the neurology service for somnolence.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, Ativan, Hydralazine, Lorazepam
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This is a bedside EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm on the left.  The right hemisphere demonstrates significant disruption of faster frequency activity, particularly in the lateral temporal regions and central temporal regions.  Mu activity is identified on the left and at the midline, but not on the right.  As the recording continues there is variability of terms of the disruption of faster frequency activity on the right and in some sections the faster frequency is disrupted throughout the right hemisphere.  EKG artifact is prominent at T2.  This drowsy patient seems to have micro-sleeps with sleep spindles.
HR:    40-60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal due to:
Marked disruption of faster frequency activity in the right hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a structural or functional process on the right.  The micro-sleeps with stage II sleep may play a role in the somnolence.  The bradycardia may also merit a clinical evaluation.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  38 year old right handed male with bipolar disease, gait disorder and possible seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Trazodone, Cymbalta, Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 8.3 Hz alpha rhythm in what is a relatively low voltage EEG.  Hyperventilation produces a small amount of slowing.  Features of drowsiness include slowing rolling eye movements. Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record.
HR:    90 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Mild slowing of the alpha rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The slowing of the alpha rhythm may be due to the patient's medications.  No epileptiform features were identified.  If seizures are an
important consideration, a follow-up study capturing deeper stages of sleep can be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  22 year old right handed female with a history of seizures with increased number of seizures recently, refractory to multiple medications, also with a history of nonepileptic spells.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Lamotrigine, Zonisamide.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure classification.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long-term monitoring EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and EKG electrodes.  Video recording was also performed.  Continuous spike detection software as well as seizure detection software along with the patient's alarms and nurses' notes were used to review the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9 to 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient has a normal amount of frontocentral beta.  No activating procedures were performed.  The patient was recorded in stage I and stage II and deep slow-wave sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Only during sleep, some focal sharp waves were seen with a large field at FB2/F8 with small bursts seen rarely.
DAY 1:  Two events occurred during the first day of recording.  One occurred at 1:48 p.m. and the other one occurred at 11:07 p.m.  During both of them, the patient suddenly stated that she did not feel well and suddenly started having right arm shaking and moving side to side with her eyes closed with irregular body motions and hand shaking.  During the first event, she would also lift her legs and move side to side while unresponsive.  This lasted about 2 to 3 minutes, then stopped and the patient was back to herself.  The second one was of similar clinical presentation; however, the flapping and shifting side to side was much more aggressive and severe.  This lasted about 3 minutes.  During both events, the EEG appeared to remain normal with no epileptiform activity or EEG correlate to these events.
LONG TERM MONITORING – 12-57 – 05/09/2012 TO 05/10/2012
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Day 2:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm which reaches 9 Hz with a normal frontal central beta.  This patient is recorded in stage I, stage II, stage III, and REM sleep.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  During sleep, specifically stage II to III, the patient appears to have some frequent bifrontal sharp waves at FP2, as well as some more temporal sharp waves.  There is also bursts of slowing with sharply contoured activity seen with multifocal regions more frontal more temporal, but not clear if it is epileptic.
No events were captured during this 24-hour recording.
SEIZURES:  None
This is long-term, day #3, 05/09/2012 to 05/10/2012, a total of 24 hour
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Day #3.
Abnormal discharges:  As stated above, focal sharp waves seen intermittently in sleep with abrupt at times more prominent in the right frontal region at FP-2 and sometimes F4, and quickly moving toward the right temporal lobe.  At times there are sharp waves that appear to be left frontal, FP3, and sometimes they appear to be more at T6 P3.  These are at times all seen in complexes that last for 1 to 2 seconds, usually mainly in sleep.
SEIZURES:
Complex partial seizure #1.  occurred on 05/09/2012 at 12:31 p.m. and ended at 12:34 p.m., with a total duration of 2 minutes and 14 seconds.  Description of seizure:  The patient is laying on her left side while asleep.  Suddenly she arouses, opens her eyes, and jolts her body, then her right arm moves up and becomes tonic while her left hand becomes dystonic in a spooning fashion.  The right arm then continues to lower down and stretches forward along with the left arm while her eyes go back and her moans.  She then starts having clonic jerks of both arms and body.  The lower extremities cannot be visualized clearly in the video.  She continues to have clonic jerks while moaning and then slowly the jerks start decreasing in frequency and then they stop with the last ictal jerk on the left hand.  Afterward, she lays in bed unresponsive.  She is not tested during the entire seizure.
EEG during seizure #1:  At onset, there is a generalized attenuation of faster frequencies followed by a generalized polyspike discharge that appears to be slightly more predominant over the right hemisphere than the left with no clear area of maximality, which in about 20 seconds appears to settle on the right temporal lobe more than the left and continues to evolve in frequency and then spread to the frontal region of the right hemisphere and then seen later spreading through the frontal lobe of the left hemisphere and then generalizing and obscured by muscle artifact.  At the end of the seizure there appears to be diffuse attenuation.
Tonic-clonic seizure #2 occurred at 4:00 in the morning and ended at 4:02 in the morning.  Seizure description:  The patient again is asleep, this time laying on her right side.  The patient opens her eyes about 8 seconds into the electrographic seizure but does not move until about 30 seconds after the electrographic seizure begins.  Suddenly both hands become dystonic and stiff while stretching forward slightly, and she remains tonic with tonic stress posturing for about 20 to 30 seconds.  Afterward she starts having tonic-clonic movements of both arms while moaning repeatedly.  She continues to do this until the jerks, after increasing frequency, start decreasing in frequency and then later stop.
EEG description:  Again, at the onset of the seizure, there appears to be a slight diffuse attenuation and slowing with no clear onset but appears to have a slight right-sided predominance, although it is mainly generalized with polyspikes that appear to be somewhat temporal and frontal maximal.  As the seizure evolves in frequency, it appears to settle slightly over the right temporal lobe, then spreading quickly to the prefrontal region bilaterally and then is obscured by muscle artifact.  At the end of the seizure, there is diffuse attenuation seen.
SEIZURES #3:  Occurred at 06:13 in the morning and ended at 6:15 in the morning.  Seizure description:  The patient is again asleep and opens her eyes about 8 seconds into the seizure, but lays there still and about 20 seconds later her eyes rolled up and her both arms lift up in the air in a dystonic fashion, the right slightly more than the left, followed by stretching forward and both hands becoming dystonic, and then clonic movements increasing in frequency and then decreasing in frequency with associated grunting.  At the end, the last ictal jerk is seen on the left.  No testing was performed during this seizure, either.
EEG description:  At the onset of the seizure, again there is a diffuse slowing with a sharp wave seen, appears to be slightly maximal at T6, followed by polyspikes that appear to be more posterior than anterior and maximal maybe under the right posterotemporal region at T6 which appeared to evolve and settle mainly over T4, followed by a frontal spread and then generalized spreading and obscuration by muscle artifact.  Again, at the end of the seizure, there is diffuse slowing seen.
Day #4:
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  As previous days
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  The impression is abnormal EEG due to multifocal spikes from both hemispheres, at times with right predominance but seen in both hemispheres, as well as 3 seizures with unclear onset which appear to be generalized, at times with a right frontal slight predominance.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This long-term video monitoring unit is diagnostic of what appears to be multifocal localization related epilepsy with seizures possibly arising from the frontal and temporal regions.  In addition, the events during day 1 of recording had no EEG correlate.  As such, these events are not epileptic and are diagnostic psychogenic nonepileptic seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  23 year old woman with a previous craniotomy and VP shunt, readmitted with recurrent seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Keppra, Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and possible photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG was markedly abnormal.  The left hemisphere demonstrates a well organized pattern with 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  The right hemisphere demonstrates a breach rhythm, disruption of the alpha rhythm, sharply contoured mixed state delta, and some sharp waves at T4.  Features of drowsiness include an accentuation of the focal slowing, breach rhythm, and sharply contoured slowing in the right temple region.  In addition, as the patient's transitions in and out of drowsiness, some of this transitions a bit more posteriorly. Photic stimulation demonstrates a driving response on the left.
HR:    96 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right temporal focal slowing.
Right temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures were recorded.  This patient's epileptiform activity may be accentuated by the craniotomy defect.  Long-term monitoring will follow for this individual.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  46 year old right handed woman with sarcoid, recent meningeal biopsy for diffuse septo meningeal enhancement.  She was admitted on May 12, 2012 with 2 seizures lasting 3 minutes with incontinence, abnormal gait, and syncope.  The patient has a right frontal biopsy site.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  There was no hyperventilation or photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is excess theta noted in the background.  There are occasional bursts of shifting slowing, a bit more prominent on the right compared to the left.  The patient transitions in and out of stage I and stage II sleep.  There are bursts of rhythmic frontal delta noted in the transition in and out of sleep.  A breech rhythm is noted in the right frontal region.
HR:    66 to 90 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Excess theta.
Shifting slowing, particularly in the right hemisphere, some of which is sharply contoured, particularly at T4.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No definitive sharp waves were seen.  This EEG supports a bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function.  The FIRDA is a nonspecific finding. The shifting slowing, particularly on the right, may be correlated with this patient's imaging.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  81 year old male found, status post PEA code for 1 hour.
MEDICATIONS:  Captopril, Plavix, ASA, Famotidine
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside in using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates primarily a theta frequency pattern with 7 Hz theta.  There are portions of the record where the patient transitions to an 8 Hz pattern.  Eye blink is noted and there is evidence of an alerting or an awake pattern which is somewhat slow, but there is a definitive posterior dominant rhythm of 7 to 8 Hz in theta background.
HR:    90 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Modest background slowing in an awake patient.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  For this individual, three days following cardiac arrest, this EEG carries a positive prognosis.  Clinical evaluation is necessary to put this in the appropriate context.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  44 year old man with a right MCA infarct, episode of new onset left sided weakness.
MEDICATIONS:  Lisinopril, Baclofen, Oxycodone, Lipitor, Isordil, ASA.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in exam.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that is best seen over the left hemisphere with a frequency of 9 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 mV.  There is normal amount of frontal central beta seen over the left hemisphere.  No activating procedures were performed.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness, as well as stage I and stage II sleep.  The architectural stage I and stage II sleep is best seen most over the left hemisphere.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen continuously at F8/T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-40 mV and associated loss of faster frequency over this hemisphere, mainly over the temporal region.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Continuous focal slowing over the left hemisphere, maximal over the temporal region, in addition to lots of faster frequencies over that region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural dysfunction involving both the gray and white matter, which is consistent with the known stroke.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

The patient is recorded in wakefulness, stage 1 and stage 2 sleep.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.

IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 20 year old right handed female with a history of hydrocephalus and pre-maturity presents with new onset seizures and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using  standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures, including hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.

Mild right posterior temporal slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  75 year old man with diabetes, COPD, hypertension, CAD, CHF, on oxygen, presents with intermittent fluctuation in speech and cognition.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  The patient has continuous movement and multiple muscle electrode artifact throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 6-7 Hz which appears to be somewhat reactive to eye opening.  There is a lack of normal frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded while awake.  Photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz with an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts seen continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Mild-to-moderate generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of mild-to-moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 7 Hz.  There is some frontal central beta seen.  The patient is also recorded in wakefulness and sleep, although normal sleep architecture is not normally present, it is actually disrupted.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz and continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.

Generalized slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  49 year old right handed man with a history cocaine use with multiple seizures now confused.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Depakote, Keppra.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Multiple seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with interior and anterior single lead EKG electrode.  He patient was recorded mainly in sleep, stage I and stage II.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals no abnormal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded mainly in what appears to be sleep, but the background is not typical for normal sleep architecture.  It consists of mainly diffuse slowing in a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.  There is intermixed bursts of 12-15 Hz beta in a spindle-like appearance throughout the recording.  These bursts may last up to 1 to 5 seconds. No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slowing at 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.  There is intermittent bursts of spindles and frequency discharges seen mainly in the frontocentral region throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Mild generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which did not specifically etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  Please note that the spindle bursts seen throughout the recording may be seen in the setting of a medication effect.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 50 year old left handed man with a history of syncope versus seizures, who presents with episodes of shaking for 10 minutes with loss of consciousness with no bowel or bladder incontinence.  No record of events.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a normal amount of frontal central beta.  Activating procedures, which included photic stimulation, revealed no abnormal discharges.  The patient is recorded in drowsiness only.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen frequently at F8/T4 with an amplitude of 20-60 mV at a frequency of 2-4 Hz.  At times it become monomorphic, but not clearly rhythmic.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right anterior temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right anterior temporal region, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  A repeat EEG with capturing sleep may be helpful in elucidating the diagnosis.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  51 year old right handed male with a stroke, left hemiparesis, hepatitis B, and hepatitis C.  The patient was admitted with acute and chronic renal failure and left leg shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Coumadin
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, at times there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  The background is intermittently disrupted by generalized background slowing.  As the patient transitions in and out of sleep, there is a subtle asymmetry with disruption of the alpha rhythm on the right.   Photic stimulation elicits bilateral slowing.
HR:    90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Intermittent bursts of generalized focal slowing.
Occasional disruption of the alpha rhythm on the right relative to the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is more supportive of a metabolic process.  The subtle focal features may be correlated with imaging.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  50 year old woman admitted on the 15th after cardiac arrest, coded for 45 minutes at home and then 30 minutes in the emergency room.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The integrity of the system is reviewed and the EEG can be reviewed in the ECS montage.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  No electrocerebral activity was identified.  Stimulation of the patient did not produce a change in the EEG.  There was no reactivity or variability.
HR:    120 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Absence of cerebral activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG does not meet criteria for declaration of brain death, as the duration of the study does not meet the requirement for 30 minutes.  Despite this, there was no brain activity identified.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  27 year old right handed male with epilepsy.  The patient missed his seizures medications on the 19th as he was n.p.o. for hernia repair and had 3 seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Keppra, Lovenox
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This was an awake, postictal individual.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates frequent, nearly continuous left anterior temporal spike and slow wave, and sharp and slow wave complexes in wakefulness.  The majority of these are maximum at T1, some spreading to S7.  The sharp waves and spikes build up and they are sometimes periodic in nature and/or are associated with rhythmic delta from the left temporal region.  Hyperventilation and drowsiness both seem to accentuate these. The right hemisphere demonstrates mild background slowing, but there is a 7 Hz mean rhythm and an 8 Hz alpha rhythm.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta and theta as well as occasional vertex waves.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR:    108 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Prominent, left anterior temporal sharp waves and spikes noted in wakefulness and drowsiness.
Left temporal rhythmic focal slowing.
Mild background disorganization on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a highly epileptiform-looking EEG.  Ongoing vigilance is appropriate to make sure that this patient is improving after 3 seizures.  The left temporal sharp waves were noted o prior EEGs.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 53 year old right handed woman with epilepsy, alcohol abuse and alcohol withdrawal seizures..
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Lovenox.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the patient appears to be jittery with a fair amount of eye movement.  There is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm identified on the left.  It appears to be disrupted on the right.  As the patient transitions to sleep, faster frequency activity drops out on the right before the left and there are rare right central temporal sharp waves observed.  Hyperventilation does not significantly activate the record.  As the recording continues, the patient is awake and quite jittery.  The disrupt alpha on the background is a bit more prominent. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response more prominent on the left than the right.
HR:    104 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Disrupted alpha rhythm on the right.
Right focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  Comparison with previous EEGs may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  55 year old woman with right MCA infarct on June 18, status post t-PA.  Hemorrhagic conversion.  Right craniotomy on June 19.  Persistently high intracranial pressure.  Previously treated with propofol and fentanyl which failed to control her ICP, now transitioned to alternative therapy.  Massive right MCA infarct with edema.
MEDICATIONS:  Fentanyl, Propofol, Versed, Vecuronium, Hydralazine, Mannitol, Labetalol, Protonix
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  The right hemisphere is essentially suppressed with lower voltage delta.  The left hemisphere demonstrates intermittent, sharply contoured theta, and some faster frequency activity.  There is an aspect of periodicity to the bursts of cerebral function on the left.   Stimulation of the patient does not activate the record.
HR:    72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Markedly abnormal background.
Essentially suppressed pattern from the right.
Markedly slow and attenuated pattern on the left with intermittent, somewhat periodic activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a severe bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral dysfunction affecting the right hemisphere more than the left.  No seizures were noted.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  38 year old left handed woman with epilepsy since childhood.  Seizures described as warmth in the head and then the patient has rocking movements or foot tapping.  Last seizure was June 8.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamotrigine, Topamax, Carbamazepine.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the EEG is acceptably organized, but as the patient becomes drowsy, there are higher amplitude, paroxysmal bursts.  There is sharply contoured activity in the frontal regions bilaterally.  In addition, focal spikes are noted in the left temporal region.  These are accentuated by hyperventilation.  EKG artifact is picked up in the right temporal region and there are some subtle, broadly contoured right temporal sharp waves. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.  In addition, around the time of photic stimulation, there are some discrete bifrontal sharp waves not clearly elicited by photic stimulation.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Background disorganization.
Intermittent, paroxysmal bursts of rhythmic slowing.
Left anterior temporal sharp waves.
Suspicious underlying bifrontal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Previous EEGs were not available for comparison.  Although there are left temporal spikes, the overall pattern raises concerns about a more complex epilepsy then temporal lobe epilepsy syndrome.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  62 year old woman status post code in the field, intubated on June 24, 2012 at 1848.  Initially moving all extremities, now with only eye movements, COPD, oxygen dependent.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Simvastatin, Zosyn, Vancomycin, Flagyl, Solu Medrol
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is intubated and comatose.  The technologist observes that the patient has intermittent eye movements.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates primarily a burst suppression pattern with a markedly suppressed pattern.  In the bursts of activity that occur, there are bursts of high amplitude, sharply contoured faster frequency activity.  Some of these bursts begin on the left.  The duration of the bursts varies from 3 seconds to 10-15 seconds.  Many of the bursts, particularly those with high amplitude activity, are associated with eye blink.  At the beginning of a burst there are typically three eye blinks.  In addition, in some of the discharges when the patient has another high voltage burst within that burst, eye blink will be seen again. Later sections of the record demonstrate a burst and attenuation pattern with lower voltage theta, but the initial sections are markedly suppressed.
HR:    120 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Burst suppression pattern.
What appears to be an ictal pattern with consistent pattern of eye blinking with high voltage discharges.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a very worrisome pattern, 18 hours following cardiac arrest.  Because of the correlation between the discharges on the EEG and the patient's clinical symptoms, this EEG should be considered ictal.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 61 year old male with a past history of stroke and seizure, left MCA infarct.  Cardiac arrest 06/22 for 9 minutes.  The patient recovered but 2 days ago had right gaze deviation with left hand shaking.  Treated with Ativan.  Persistent obtundation.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Lamictal, Ciprofloxacin,. Lipitor, Dilantin
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is intubated and somnolent.  Stimulation of the patient was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The overall EEG is diffusely slow with a lower voltage, rhythmic 7 Hz theta pattern and smaller amounts of delta.  Stimulation of the patient produces beta spindles on some occasions and on other occasions produces an arousal with both muscle of faster frequency activity.  There are shifting asymmetries observed.  On some occasions the left appears to be slower than the right but there is also a asymmetry in the degree of muscle artifact.  Stimulation of the patient produces eye opening and movement artifact.
HR:    78 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The background slowing is a nonspecific finding and may be due to medications, toxic or metabolic factors or even post ictal state.  Asymmetries in this record may have been masked by the amount of muscle artifact.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  61 year old gentleman with stroke, left MCA infarct, recurrent status epilepticus, cardiac arrest due January 22, 2012 for 9 minutes, followed by right gaze deviation with left hand shaking.  Evaluate for recurrent seizures.  Persistent obtundation.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Lamictal, Dopamine, Dobutamine, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement.  The patient is poorly responsive and has a tracheostomy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  Multiple electrographic seizures are noted with high amplitude epileptiform activity from the left hemisphere, typically maximum in the left frontal central region, but with a generous field of spread.
The spikes seems to be maximum at C3, but fast activity is seen throughout the left frontal central region with more periodic activity left frontal.  In some locations there seems to be a posterior to anterior lag or even more than one epileptiform focus in the left temporal region, but the ictal driver seems to be in the left frontal central region.
Seizures are typically on the duration of 1-2 minutes.  Characteristic frequency of evolution of the seizures was observed.
Despite the marked background slowing, the patient seems to be somewhat responsive.  During the seizures, he has head turning to the right, but not really a forced deviation, more of a more gentle head turning.
When he is not seizing, he does seem to demonstrate some head control and some spontaneous movement on the left when the seizures stop.
The background EEG is otherwise markedly slow bilaterally.
HR:    120 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
A status epilepticus pattern with multiple, repetitive seizures from the left hemisphere.
Sharp waves and spikes in the left.
Intermittent burst suppressed pattern when the patient is not seizing.
Some generalized periodic complexes observed in the interictal section of the record.
Some posterior predominant generalized periodic discharges also noted in the interictal period.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient has previously been evaluated for status epilepticus out of the left hemisphere.  This EEG may demonstrate some features which are due to anoxic encephalopathy, as well as the ictal pattern.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  75 year old right handed female with a history of left MCA stroke and residual right-sided weakness and aphasia who had seizures causing right facial twitching lasting 30 minutes on various occasions in October 2011.  Follow-up EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Simvastatin, ASA, Plavix.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using a standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation only was performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 8.5-9 Hz which appears to be reactive to eye opening.  The patient is recorded mainly in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation which were performed revealed no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen very frequently to almost continuously at S7/T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left anterior temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region which is consistent with the known stroke.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  Please note this is different from the previous EEG recorded on July 30, 2010 which showed some left temporal sharp waves.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  59 year old right handed woman with seizures 2 weeks ago, diabetes, hypertension, left-sided CVA, and past history of nonepileptic seizures with long-term monitoring in 2006.  Seizures at that time were characterized by vocalization, crying, rotatory movements, and jiggling movements.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Topamax
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there was a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm.  This is a clearly focal EEG with focal slowing in the left hemisphere, maximum in the mid-to-posterior temporal region.  There are simple T5 and T3 sharp waves noted in the background.  There are occasional spikes which are left anterior temporal followed by a T2 more subtle spike.  Hyperventilation accentuates the focal slowing with more rhythmic theta-delta in the left frontotemporal region and attenuation of faster frequency activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  The alpha drops our earlier on the left than the right.  Other features of drowsiness include a transition to more left mid-to-posterior temporal focal slowing and sharp waves. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving on the right.
HR:    84 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left temporal focal slowing, often posterior temporal.
Sharp waves in the left temporal region including anterior temple or posterior temple, and sometimes with the field extending to T2.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are similar so many previous EEGs.  This patient has consistently demonstrated focal features and left temporal sharp waves but when seizures have been recorded both behavioral characteristics and EEG patterns have not demonstrated an epileptiform correlate.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  82 year old right handed woman with cardiopulmonary disease, admitted with a syncopal event.  She felt dizzy, then fell and hit her head.  She presented confused with left facial droop, evaluate for new stroke.
MEDICATIONS:  ASA, Metoprolol, Lisinopril, Digoxin, Atorvastatin, Pantoprazole
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  This was a challenging EEG for a patient who was coughing and had difficulty cooperating while awake.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat slow and disorganized with a 6 to 7 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is an asymmetry.  There is a disruption of the theta frequency activity on the left and a little bit more slowing on the left.  As the patient becomes drowsy, the EEG is more symmetric and synchronous with more of a pattern of rhythmic theta and delta.
HR:    78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Marked background disorganization.
Slow pattern while awake.
Superimposed focal slowing with disruption of faster frequency activity on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function affecting both gray and white matter.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old man with change in mental status, found on the side of the road, unresponsive with septic shock, acute kidney injury, upper GI bleed, noted to have right arm shaking, right eye deviation, and was placed on pentobarbital for cerebral edema and seizure monitoring.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Pentobarbital, Phenylephrine, Dopamine.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures and pentobarbital coma.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during unresponsiveness.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG reveals no abnormal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  Overall, it reveals a very low amplitude diffuse slow record with an overriding EKG artifact and no clear cerebral activity.  There is no normal sleep architecture and no activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Almost completely suppressed EEG with no cerebral activity.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Complete suppression of any normal cerebral activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of marked diffuse cerebral dysfunction with no cerebral activity which may be due, at least in part, to medication effect.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.  The findings on this EEG were reported to the consult team right after it was done.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 53 year old female with history of seizures, alcohol abuse, and noncompliance with medications, fell and was noted to not be responding appropriately and crying frequently.
MEDICATIONS:  Lorazepam, Lovenox, Morphine.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were note performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some intermittent movement artifact throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffuse slow background with slow posterior dominant rhythm that is best seen over the left hemisphere, at best reaches 6-7 Hz, which appears to be somewhat reactive to eye opening.  There is no normal sleep architecture.  Some frontal central beta is seen over the left hemisphere, but overall the background was consistent with theta delta slowing.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen continuously at T6 with a large amplitude and rhythmically at 1 Hz consistent with periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLED's).
Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz in wakefulness.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right posterior temporal PLED's.
Mild to moderate generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural dysfunction and acute irritability in the right posterior temporal region, which has a high correlation with seizures arising from that area.  In addition, there is evidence of mild to moderate
diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology and may be due at least in part to medication effects.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 54-year-old woman with a history of hyperlipidemia, hypertension, seizures, schizophrenia, and CAD, presents with altered mental status, had acute change in mental status and was minimally responsive.
MEDICATIONS:  Lorazepam, Protonix, Lisinopril, Percocet, Plavix, Lovenox
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded while awake.  No activating procedures were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a mildly slow background at 8 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a normal amount of frontocentral beta.  No activating procedures were performed.  The patient was recorded only in wakefulness.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Mild excessive theta in wakefulness at 5 to 7 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction and slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  63 year old gentleman with renal failure on hemodialysis.  Past history of alcohol abuse, gunshot wound to the right eye, now admitted with right intraventricular hemorrhage requiring ventriculostomy.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Labetalol, Ativan
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient was intubated and poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a diffusely slow, low voltage record with a mixture of slower delta and smaller amounts of theta.  Scant alpha frequency activity was noted. There is an intermittent subtle asymmetry with a bit more faster frequency activity noted on the left.  This is less apparent in sections of the record with EKG or muscle artifact.  Stimulation of the patient occurs with the patient coughing or with auditory stimulation and produces a bit of the asymmetry with a bit more faster frequency activity on the left.  This is a soft finding.
HR:    126 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Marked generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  Subtle focal features noted in this record were challenged by the amount of background artifact. This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  79 year old gentleman with a history of severe alcohol use, now brought in unresponsive after a single witnessed general tonic-clonic convulsion.  The patient currently remains unresponsive.
MEDICATIONS:  Lorazepam, Labetolol
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to superior frequency amplitude gradient.  Large portions of the EEG consist of diffuse significant muscle artifact that obscures large portions of the EEG.  Visible underlying activity consists of a mixture of low amplitude polymorphic theta mixed with faster frequencies.  During periods of relative quiescence the recording consists of bursts of diffuse spindle like wave forms mixed with frequent periods of brief 1 to 2 second discontinuities.  No clear epileptiform discharges are captured.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  Increase in the heart rate is noted on the single EKG lead at the end of the recording.
FINDINGS:
Moderate diffuse slowing.
Excess beta.
Background discontinuity.
No electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal 22 minute EEG due to diffuse background slowing and periods of discontinuity.  These findings indicate nonspecific cerebral dysfunction, that in this case could partially be related to medication affect.  Excess beta is likely related to medication affect, benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  No clear electrographic seizures are captured.  These findings were conveyed to the primary team at the time of the dictation.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old right handed woman with a history of seizures and alcohol abuse, now with intermittent episodes of confusion and agitation, concerning for seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Vimpat 50 mg b.i.d.
CONDITIONS OF RECORDING:  Digital video continuous EEG performed was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is a right to left interhemispheric asymmetry.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the left hemisphere consists of a low to moderate amplitude 9 to 10 Hz alpha activity with preserved anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the right hemisphere consists of 79 Hz activity with weak anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  During sleep, sleep spindles and at least epoch of REM sleep is captured.  There is additional continuous polymorphic theta and delta activity over the right hemisphere, most notably over the right temporal region.  Independent right anterior temporal frontocentral epileptiform discharges and additional independent right midtemporal as well as independent right posterior quadrant/occipital epileptiform discharges are captured.  Phase reversal occurs over F8, T6, and O2 electrodes, respectively.  As the recording progresses, frequency of right occipital/right posterior quadrant epileptiform discharges increases.  A single episode concerning for an electrographic seizure is captured.  It starts at about 10:45 p.m., lasting until about 10:50 p.m.  It is characterized by rhythmic slow delta activity observed over the right hemisphere, most notably over the right temple region with embedded sharp waves over T6 and O2 electrodes.  The patient appears to wake up at the beginning of the seizure.  Also, there is an increase in the heart rate observed in a single EKG lead from about 120 beats a minute to about 130 to 140 beats a minute.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.
FINDINGS:
Focal slowing over the right hemisphere, most notably over the right temple region.
Independent epileptiform discharges over the right anterior temporal central region, right midtemporal region, and right posterior quadrant/occipital region.  The frequency of these epileptiform discharges increases as the recording progresses.
Likely a single electrographic right hemispheric, primarily right midtemporal/right posterior quadrant electrographic seizure is captured at approximately 10:45 p.m.  This seizure lasted approximately 5 minutes.  There is an associated increase in the heart rate during the event, as well as the patient awakening at the beginning of the event.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal continuous, about 15 hour, video EEG due to:
Continuous moderate right hemispheric slowing, most notable over the right midtemporal region.
Independent right anterior frontocentral, right midtemporal, and right posterior quadrant/occipital region epileptiform discharges.
Likely a single approximately 5-minute focal right hemispheric, primarily right midtemporal/right posterior quadrant electrographic seizure.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   These findings indicate a significant dysfunction over the right hemisphere, likely structural in etiology with increased epileptogenic potential.  These findings were conveyed to the Neurology consulting team at the time of the review.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old right handed man status post traumatic brain injury and seizures, as well as traumatic subarachnoid and status post bitemporal craniectomy, as well as a history of anxiety, depression, memory disorders, here for follow up of his seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Topamax, Zolpidem, Percocet, Citalopram, Keppra, Gabapentin
REASON FOR STUDY:  Blacking out.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with additional anterior temporal and single EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while awake.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  The patient has frequent myogenic artifact of the temporalis muscles on both temporal lobes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is frontal central beta.  Activating procedures, including photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.  The patient was only recorded in wakefulness.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen continuously over both temporal lobes, slightly more over the right temporal lobe than the left at T4 more than T3, at a frequency of 2-4 Hz, with an amplitude of 20-60 mV.  In that same area there is an increase of larger amplitude and faster frequencies seen bilaterally consistent with a breech rhythm.  At times there is some sharply contoured wave forms in this region, but not clearly epileptiform.  However, the limited quality of the EEG due to the muscle artifact sometimes obscures clear identification of these waves forms.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Independent bilateral temporal continuous slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural cerebral dysfunction in both mid temporal regions, which is consistent with the known trauma  and hemorrhage.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.
This patient had a previous EEG on April 19, 2012 which showed focal slow waves at T4/C4 and some generalized slowing, which is slightly different than the EEG today.  A previous EEG on March 22, 2012 had shown generalized slowing and some more slowing on the left hemisphere than the right.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  70 year old right handed woman with a history of Alzheimer's, hypertension, hyperlipidemia who presents with right-sided weakness as well as episodes of head turning to the right.  She is shaking all extremities.  No confused and less responsive than usual.
MEDICATIONS:  Protonix, ASA, Heparin, Hydralazine, Lorazepam, Metoprolol, Zocor, Simvastatin, Cyanocobalamin, Ceftriaxone, Keppra.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using a standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while poorly unresponsive.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some movement artifact throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture and no activating procedures were performed.  Overall, the background is consistent with delta frequency wave forms that become very monomorphic at times.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen periodically at 1-2 Hz in the F3/P3 electrodes becoming very rhythmic but not clearly evolving and consistent with periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLEDs).
Focal slow waves in the F3 region.
generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz and amplitude 20-60 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left frontal parietal periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges.
Slowing in addition to generalized slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG revealed evidence of acute structural focal dysfunction and irritability in the left frontoparietal region which has a high correlation with seizures arising from that region.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebellar dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  It may be, in part, related to her Alzheimer dementia disease.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  58 year old right handed man with a history of a gunshot wound to the head 20 years ago, seizures, hypertension and sarcoid, who presented to the hospital after having 3 seizures. He was noted to have periodic twitching in the ED, but was alert, following commands and verbal.  He was found to have an acute intraventricular hemorrhage.
MEDICATIONS:  Protonix, Pantoprazole, Ativan.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement with the addition of anterior temporal single lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a mildly slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 8 Hz which appears to be somewhat reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures were not performed.  At one point the patient appears to have some sleep architecture reminiscent of stage I sleep with some vertex movements decreased, muscle activity and later on what appears to be stage II with sleep spindles.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen in the left hemisphere maximal at T3 continuously throughout the recording at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
Focal slow waves seen intermittently at T4 at a frequency 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 mV.
Generalized slowing at 5-10 Hz seen throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:   None
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left mid temporal continuous slowing.
Some right mid temporal slowing.
Mild generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left mid temporal region which is consistent with the known gunshot wound and hemorrhage.  In addition, there is mild focal cerebral dysfunction in the right mid temporal region as well as some mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, both of which are nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  75 year old woman who is vent dependent and trached postoperative day 21 of lung biopsy with a waxing and waning mental status.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded while poorly responsive.  Activating procedures were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There was no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz seen continuously throughout the recording at an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.
Triphasic waves seen at 0.5-1 Hz with anterior predominance seen almost continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:    None.
HR:     114 and irregular
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slowing.
Triphasic waves.  Please note that sometimes there is some sharply contoured right temporal and right frontal components, but not clearly epileptiform.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which are nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.  Please note that the finding of triphasics has a high correlation with metabolic encephalopathy possibly related to liver disease.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 61-year-old woman who had a TIA and a  seizure in August of 2012.  Left-sided weakness, walks with a cane.  The patient also has headaches with a tingling sensation throughout the body.  These episodes occur without loss of consciousness.
MEDICATIONS:  Lisinopril, hydrochlorothiazide, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was completed using  standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The awake EEG is abnormal.  There is an asymmetry.  The alpha rhythm in the left hemisphere is slow at 7.5 Hz.  In contrast, the right hemisphere demonstrates little in the way of alpha activity.  The right hemisphere demonstrates globally, slower activity with a mixture of theta and smaller amounts of delta.  The left hemisphere also has a slow alpha rhythm and a bit of background theta.  Occasional bursts of shifting arrhythmic delta are noted from the left or right hemisphere.  As the patient becomes drowsy, the EEG becomes a little bit more rhythmic and the asymmetry on the right is a bit more apparent.  The focal slowing from the right hemisphere may be seen in the frontotemporal or the centroparietal regions.  In this sharply contoured background, there are subtle, right frontal sharp waves noted.
Photic stimulation did not significantly activate the record.  Heart rate 64 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
An asymmetry with more significant focal slowing on the right.
Mild disorganization on the left.
Shifting slowing.
In the sharply contoured background, rare subtle right frontal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a structural abnormality on the right, but a bihemispheric process may be considered (ischemic cerebrovascular disease).  The subtle sharp waves raise the possibility of a focal mechanism for seizures.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 57-year-old man with a history of stroke, right temporal, and seizures, now with recurrent seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Atorvastatin, carbamazepine, omeprazole, lisinopril, and amlodipine.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some electrode artifact, mainly over the left hemisphere, seen continuously.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 to 10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal sharp waves seen intermittently at F7/T3 during wakefulness and drowsiness, as well as F8/T4, also during wakefulness and drowsiness (slightly more on the left than the right).
Focal slow waves seen at F8/T4 at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts, almost continuously throughout the recording.  In addition, there is some intermittent F7/T3 focal slowing at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and amplitude of 20 to 50 microvolts.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to bilateral anterior temporal sharp waves as well as independent focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from either anterior temporal lobes.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction which is independently seen in both anterior temporal regions, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology.  No seizures were seen.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  23 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 63-year-old woman with past medical history of atrial fibrillation and metastatic ovarian cancer who underwent left frontal craniotomy on 08/21/2012.  She now presents with expressive aphasia and generalized weakness.
MEDICATIONS:  Dexamethasone, Lovenox and metoprolol.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and  T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The background consists of low to moderate amplitude  polymorphic mixture of theta and delta with occasional triphasic wave forms.  Additional intermittent theta and delta are captured over the left frontocentral region.   Sleep is not captured.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  No electrographic seizures are seen.  A single EKG lead demonstrates irregular heart rate with a heart rate up to 150 beats per minute.
FINDINGS:
Moderate diffuse slowing.
Focal left frontocentral slowing.
Cardiac arrhythmia.
No electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 23-minute awake only EEG due to moderate diffuse slowing and focal left frontocentral slowing and triphasic wave forms.  Diffuse slowing indicates etiologically nonspecific cerebral dysfunction that in his case could partially be related to toxic metabolic etiology.  Triphasic waves are observed in different forms of encephalopathy.  Focal left frontocentral slowing could be secondary to an underlying cerebral dysfunction that is structural in etiology and is consistent with the patient's history of left frontal craniotomy.  Cardiac arrhythmia with heart rate up to 150 beats a minute is noted in the single EKG lead.  No clear electrographic seizures are captured.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  22 minutes
DESCRIPTION OF RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10/20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.
HISTORY:  The patient is a 51-year-old man with a prior history of left MCA territory stroke who now presents with a chief complaint of chest pain and syncope.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, nitroglycerin, aspirin, Lovenox, Tylenol, Plavix and Lasix.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated moderate amplitude 9 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  Continuous EMG artifact is present over the bifrontal regions.  Intermittent drowsiness is captured.  Stage II sleep is not recorded.  Intermittent fluctuating excessive theta is observed over the bitemporal region, significantly more prominent over the left temporal leads.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Photic stimulation results in no change in background.  Regular heart rate is noted in the single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:  Shifting mild to moderate bitemporal slowing, more common over the left temporal region.  No stage II sleep.
No clear epileptiform discharges.  Regular heart rate.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal 22-minute awake and drowsy EEG due to mild to moderate shifting bitemporal slowing that is more pronounced over the left temporal region.  This finding indicates a nonspecific underlying cerebral dysfunction that is more prominent over the left temporal region.  In a patient with a prior left MCA territory stroke, more pronounced left temporal slowing is consistent with his history of prior stroke.  No epileptiform discharges are captured; however, stage II sleep is not recorded.  A regular heart rate is noted in the single EKG lead.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 to 10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a normal amount of frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation produce no abnormal discharges.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.

Seizures:  None.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  21 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 53-year-old man brought after having 2 witnessed episodes of generalized tonic/clonic convulsions.  The patient received Versed and Ativan.
MEDICATIONS:
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  During maximal wakefulness, the posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated 10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient that is less well preserved over the left hemisphere.  Intermittent polymorphic theta and delta activity are captured over the left frontal/anterior temporal region.  Additional faster frequencies are captured over the left frontal leads.  During sleep, vertex waves, sleep spindles and K complexes are captured.  Sleep architecture is more pronounced over the left hemisphere.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.

FINDINGS:
Intermittent focal moderate slowing over the left frontal/anterior temporal region.
Breach artifact over the left anterior temporal/frontal central region.
Prominence of sleep architecture over the left hemisphere.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal 21-minute awake and asleep EEG due to intermittent moderate focal slowing over the left anterior temporal/frontal region.  This finding indicates underlying cerebral dysfunction that could be structural in etiology.  Breach artifact indicates a defect in the skull.  No clear epileptiform discharges were captured.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does not preclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 10-11 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal amount of frontal central beta, slightly seen more over the left hemisphere than the right.
Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 53-year-old woman with epilepsy and alcohol abuse, recurrent hospitalizations for medication nonadherence and exacerbation of her epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was awake and drowsy.  She had a great deal of muscle and movement artifact, and was poorly cooperative.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  It was a challenging EEG.  There is intrahemispheric asymmetry.  There is prominent disruption of faster frequency activity in the right hemisphere with a periodic complex in the right hemisphere with variability, typically right occipital, but sometimes maximum T6 or P4.  No clinical seizures were observed, but the periodic activity waxes and wanes and, in fact, when the patient is a bit more active with muscle artifact there is clearly more theta in the right hemisphere.  The left hemisphere is also slow with excess theta.  Volume conduction of the epileptiform activity was noted on the left.
The patient's chewing muscles were not associated with epileptiform activity, but they were associated with an arousal.
Heart rate 96 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Prominent arrhythmic delta activity in the right hemisphere, particularly as the patient drifts off to sleep.
Periodic complexes in the right occipital temporal region with some variability and with generous field of spread.
Slowing on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This tracing is similar to this patient's previous EEGs.  Of note, it is not as slow as the previous EEG monitoring session last month. Overall, this EEG supports a highly epileptogenic focus in the right hemisphere.
