CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 27-year-old woman with possible epilepsy, multiple suicide attempts, drug abuse.  The patient is admitted to the hospital after being found unconsciousness in bed for an unknown period of time.
MEDICATIONS:  Lovenox, antibiotics, Tylenol, Ativan.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The patient seems quite drowsy.  Despite this, in wakefulness, there is a posterior dominant rhythm of 7 Hz.  There is some shifting slowing noted in the background, as well as FIRDA.  The patient transitions in and out of stage II sleep with vertex waves, K-complexes, and spindles.
Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.  The patient is drifting in and out of sleep during photic stimulation.
Heart rate:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
Background slowing.
Slowing of the alpha rhythm.
Rare FIRDA.
Rare shifting slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were noted.  The pattern identified is a nonspecific pattern and can be seen in encephalopathy due to many different causes.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  Approximately 2 hours.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 51-year-old woman with a history of metastatic breast cancer who now presents with subacute change in mental status in the setting of fevers.  EEG is performed to rule out clinical seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Keppra, and antibiotics.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  A single EKG lead was used, as well.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  There is right to left interhemispheric asymmetry with slower waveforms at lower amplitudes over the left hemisphere.  The background consists of polymorphic low to moderate amplitude, mixture of theta and delta activity and abundant triphasic wave forms while the patient is awake.  By the end of the recording, the patient appears asleep; however, no normal sleep architecture is captured.  There are no clear epileptiform discharges or electrographic seizures.
FINDINGS:
Moderate diffuse slowing.
Focal left hemispheric slowing and voltage attenuation.
Abundant triphasic wave forms.
No electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 2-hour continuous video EEG due to moderate diffuse slowing, focal left hemispheric slowing at lower voltages, and abundant triphasic wave forms.  These findings indicate nonspecific cerebral dysfunction that is moderate in degree and at least partially related to toxic metabolic disturbances.  Focal slowing an attenuation over the left hemisphere indicates left hemispheric dysfunction that could be structural in etiology.  Triphasic wave forms are seen in nonspecific encephalopathy.  There were no clear electrographic seizures.

DATE OF RECORDING:  10/31/2012 from approximately 4:30 p.m. until 11/01/2012, approximately 7 a.m.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 51-year-old woman with past medical history of metastatic breast cancer, with right parietal lobe resection of the metastasis performed several months ago, now presents with several days of a significant decline in her mental status.  Continuous EEG is performed to rule out subclinical seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin and Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Video was enabled.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  During arousal, the background consists of a mixture of polymorphic low-to-moderate amplitude theta, delta, and abundant triphasic waveforms.  These triphasic waveforms have an anterior-to-posterior lag.  They are frontally predominant, and more predominant over the right hemisphere.  During brief periods of sleep, no normal sleep architecture is present, and there are occasional periods of brief discontinuity lasting approximately 1 second.  Additionally, polymorphic delta activity at lower voltages is captured over the left hemisphere.  There were no clear electrographic seizures.
FINDINGS:
Moderate diffuse slowing.
Focal left hemispheric slowing and attenuation.
Abundant triphasic waveforms.
No electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal continuous video EEG, lasting approximately 14-1/2 hours.  The EEG is abnormal due to moderate diffuse slowing, focal left hemispheric slowing and attenuation and abundant triphasic waveforms that are more prominent over the right hemisphere.  These findings indicate moderate cerebral dysfunction that is nonspecific in etiology, but could partially be related to toxic metabolic causes.  Focal slowing and attenuation over the left hemisphere could indicate a structural lesion over that region.  Additionally, discrepancies in the degree of slowing and amplitudes could also be related to a breach artifact present over the right hemisphere.  Triphasic waveforms indicate nonspecific encephalopathy.  No clear electrographic seizures are captured.  These findings were conveyed to the primary team.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 63-year-old man with a history of an intracerebral hemorrhage who presents with a change in mental status.
MEDICATIONS:  Compazine.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some frontal muscle artifact on the right.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 8-8.5 Hz intermittently which appears to be reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontocentral beta seen best over the left hemisphere.
Photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
The patient appears to be in stage I sleep at one point in the recording.
Heart rate 84.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen continuously at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
Focal slow waves seen intermittently over F7/T3.  These are seen at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts, again seen intermittently.
Mild excessive theta in wakefulness at a frequency of 5-7 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts seen throughout the recording in limited wakefulness.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to continuous right frontal slowing in addition to intermittent left anterior temporal slowing and mild generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral structural dysfunction in the right frontal region including almost the entire right hemisphere, which is consistent with a known intracerebral hemorrhage.  In addition, there is some left anterior temporal focal slowing as well as some mild generalized slowing, both of which are nonspecific in regards etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.

TYPE OF STUDY:  Routine EEG.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 50-year-old ambidextrous gentleman with history of right subcortical CVA with hemorrhagic transformation and pre-existing epilepsy with left frontotemporal encephalomalacia who presents for a preop EEG for right carotid endarterectomy.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include Dilantin, nortriptyline, aspirin, lisinopril, Tricor, and fluoxetine.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the lab using a standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to one channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation are performed to see tracing captures wakefulness only.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was asymmetric and characterized by 9-10 Hz in frequency, 30-40 microvolts in amplitude seen in the left occipital region and 8-8.5 Hz on the right side which attenuated with eye opening.  There was right hemispheric slowing in theta frequency and attenuation with loss of faster frequencies noted throughout the study. There were intermittent focal slowing in the left frontal and anterior temporal regions consisting of 5-6 Hz theta frequency activity with 30-40 microvolt amplitude lasting for 1-2 seconds, occasionally with a field to the left anterior and mid temporal region.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple/frequencies and result in no driving response. No epileptiform activity with seizures were seen in the study.  Heart rate was 90-100 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing wakefulness only due to:
Right hemispheric attenuation and slowing with loss of faster frequencies.
Intermittent left frontotemporal slowing during wakefulness.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Diffuse attenuation and loss of faster frequencies in the right hemispheric could be seen in the structural lesions of the underlying cerebral cortex or fluid accumulation in the extra-axial space.  Right hemispheric slowing is suggestive of subcortical structure or functional abnormalities. Focal left frontal and temporal slowing could be suggestive of an underlying structural abnormality in the left hemisphere or left frontotemporal dysfunction.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No epileptiform abnormalities were seen in this record. This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.
Please note that the patient is tachycardic.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 36-year-old man with a past medical history of hepatitis, HIV, and a possible prior stroke in 2010, as well as seizures.  Seizures are described as tonic-clonic activity of the upper extremities with associated loss of consciousness and postictal confusion.
CURRENT MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Neurontin, Celexa, methadone, HIV medications.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of low to moderate amplitude polymorphic 9 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  The anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient is present, but weak.  Additional diffuse polymorphic theta activity is captured.  During drowsiness and sleep, symmetrical vertex waves and brief sleep spindles are captured.  Hyperventilation produces mild diffuse symmetrical background slowing.  Photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple frequencies.
FINDINGS:
Mild diffuse slowing.
Brief stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and asleep 21-minute EEG due to mild diffuse slowing.  This finding indicates etiologically nonspecific mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 76-year-old male with epilepsy following stroke in 2007, hepatitis C.  The patient was found unresponsive and then had witnessed, generalized convulsions requiring Ativan and versed, persistent postictal confusion.  The patient had a large left posterior cerebral infarct with ventriculomegaly.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, folate, Keppra, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient was poorly responsive.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  There is an asymmetry noted.  The activity on the right is lower voltage.  On the left there is a bit more arrhythmic delta activity which can be frontal central or posterior.  There are occasional sharp waves or bursts of sharply contoured slowing, maximum at F3.
With arousals there is an increase in theta frequency activity and a bit better organization on the right, but not the left.
As the patient becomes drowsy, irregular, higher amplitude focal delta is noted in the left hemisphere with variable maximum.  When the technologist performs testing on the patient, the patient wakes up and an alpha rhythm is noted at 7 Hz more so on the right than the left.
Heart rate:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Marked intrahemispheric asymmetry with higher amplitude, more irregular slowing on the left.
Sharply contoured slowing from the left hemisphere with a variable maximum.
F3 sharp waves.
No seizures were recorded.  The focal features are ipsilateral to the patient's CT abnormalities.  The sharp waves are anterior to his most prominent areas of encephalomalacia.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 67-year-old man with a past medical history of hepatitis C, cirrhosis and hepatocellular carcinoma status post chemotherapy in September of 2012.  The patient has been having a change in mental status for the last several days.
MEDICATIONS:  Current medications are insulin, nystatin, Diflucan, Protonix, CellCept, Actigall.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system, with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.   Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm reaches 8.5 Hz alpha activity.  Additional polymorphic diffuse theta activity is captured.  There is continuous blink artifact that limits interpretation of the recording.  No sleep is captured.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation results in no change in the background.
FINDINGS:
Mild diffuse slowing.
Continuous blink artifact.
No sleep.
No clear epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake only 23 minute EEG due to mild diffuse slowing.  This finding indicates etiologically nonspecific mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  Continuous blinking artifact somewhat limits interpretation of the recording since anterior slowing could have been missed.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy persists, a repeat study with stage 2 sleep may be of benefit.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 52-year-old woman who had been seizure free off seizure medications but admitted with a follow-up seizure, elevated CPK, and worsening weakness.  MRI without evidence of new stroke.  Past meningioma resection in 2003.
MEDICATIONS:  Tylenol, Tegretol, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  Hyperventilation accentuates a focal slowing in the left mid temple region.  Stage 2 includes vertex K-complexes, spindles, and POSTS.
Photic stimulation elicits a driving response bilaterally.
Heart rate 80 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:  Left mid-temporal focal slowing with somewhat rhythmic left mid-temporal delta in hyperventilation and less prominent in drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The focal slowing identified on the left is more prominent than was noted in an EEG last month.  This may be attributed to the patient's postictal state.  This is her sixth EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 67-year-old right-handed man with history of hepatitis C and cirrhosis and hepatocellular carcinoma, status post chemo, who presents with episode of confusion over the last several days.  He seems drowsy and at times obtunded.
MEDICATIONS:  Lactulose, spironolactone, and Lasix.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using the standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed. This tracing captures the patient in a confused and obtunded state.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the confused, obtunded state, there is diffuse slowing of the background consisting of 5-6 Hz theta frequency activity intermixed with 2-3 Hz delta activity.  He had 10-20 microvolts in amplitude.  There were also triphasic waves seen occasionally with a frequency of 1 to 1.5 Hz, occasionally posteriorly predominant.  There is spontaneous variability seen with increased in background frequency intermittently.  There is also reactivity seen in the form of increased background frequency on stimulating.  The patient no seizures or epileptiform activity was captured.  Heart rate was 90 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing the patient in a lethargic state due to;
Diffuse slowing of the background.
The presence of triphasic waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Diffuse slowing and triphasic waves are suggestive of either metabolic toxic, anoxic or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to the effect of medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunction.  The triphasic waves could also be due to the patient's underlying liver disease.  No epileptiform abnormalities are identified in this record.  No seizures were captured.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.  If clinically indicated, a continuous bedside EEG monitoring may be helpful.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Possible seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 74-year-old woman with a right vasoganglia lesion biopsied on December 3, had on Sunday an episode of right upper extremity jerking.  She has a past medical history of diabetes, hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and atrial fibrillation.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Decadron, phenobarbital, oxybutynin, Klonopin, ceftriaxone, Cardizem, metoprolol.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded while minimally responsive.  Activating procedures were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 6 to 7 Hz, which appears to be somewhat reactive to eye opening.  There is no normal frontocentral beta.  Overall, the background is diffusely slow in a theta-delta frequency and appears to be asymmetrically faster over the left hemisphere. The right hemisphere reveals focal slowing.  In addition, there is again generalized slowing maximally bifrontally.
Heart rate 84 and irregular.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal sharp waves seen occasionally at F4 while unresponsive.
Focal slow waves seen over the right hemisphere, maximal at F8/T4 at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 40 microvolts.
Generalized slowing at 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts seen continuously throughout the recording, but at times maximally in the bifrontal region.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to right frontal focal sharp waves, in addition to right hemispheric focal slowing, maximally seen in the anterior temporal region with additional generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from the right frontal region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right hemisphere, maximal in the anterior temporal region, which is likely due to the known mass and lesion.  Lastly, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology.  No seizures were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Hypoxic injury.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 48-year-old man found unresponsive with carbon monoxide poisoning on December 1st, with a history of hypertension and alcohol abuse, left foot ischemia, non-ST-elevation myocardial infarction, bacteremia and pneumonia.
MEDICATIONS:  Insulin, aspirin, Lovenox, vitamins, Coreg, thiamine, vancomycin, Lipitor.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  Overall, the patient's background is mainly in the theta frequently at 5-7 Hz and amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.  The patient does appear to be reactive to commands and there is variability in the EEG upon stimulation.  The patient did have photic stimulation which revealed no abnormal discharges.
Heart rate 84.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Diffuse slow waves seen at 5-7 Hz and amplitude of 20-40 microvolts continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to mild-to-moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of mild-to-moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology, but is likely related to the carbon monoxide/hypoxic injury.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 25-year-old male with a history of childhood brain tumor in the left hemisphere, status post radiation and chemotherapy.  First ever seizure today, followed by right-sided weakness.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.  The patient had already had Ativan.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was quite drowsy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG includes a breach rhythm with considerably higher amplitude activity on the left compared to the right.  As the EEG begins, the patient is asleep with generous beta of 13 Hz in the frontocentral region, but without some of the typical features of stage II sleep.  The activity on the right is lower voltage and slow.  With stimulation, there is some sharply contoured activity appearing at T5 and T1.  Higher amplitude focal delta is noted throughout the left hemisphere and varies from left frontocentral to mid to posterior temporal region.  As the patient becomes a bit sleepier, the activity on the right is lower voltage and slower.  In sleep, despite the breach rhythm, there is more of a left parietal focus.  Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
Heart rate 90 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing from the left hemisphere with variability, but in sleep much more prominent in the left parietal region.
Sharply contoured slowing in the context of a breach rhythm with suggestion of a left parietal sharp wave.
Some sharp wave contoured wave forms in the left frontocentral or frontotemporal region, as well.
In wakefulness, the background is also slow on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a structural or functional abnormality on the left, congruent with a previous tumor and surgical history.  The foci of sharply contoured slowing is more prominent in the left parietal region in sleep, but is a little bit more anteriorly when the patient is stimulated.  The bilateral background slowing may be due to a diffuse brain process or postictal state.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 52-year-old man with past medical history of traumatic brain injury and seizures, also subarachnoid hemorrhoid, status post craniotomy on the right.  The patient is now with an episode of blacking out.
MEDICATIONS:  Percocet, Keppra, Neurontin, Topamax.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20  system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.   Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well formed and modulated moderate amplitude 9 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  Intermittent brief drowsiness is captured and is characterized by increase in the amount of diffuse theta activity. Intermittent polymorphic theta activity is captured over the right frontal temporal central region.  Additional faster frequencies are captured over the right frontal central region.
Hyperventilation was not performed.
Step photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.
A regular rate is noted on the single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
Intermittent mild right frontal temporal central slowing.
No stage 2 sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
Breach over the right frontal central region.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and intermittently drowsy EEG due to intermittent mild right frontal temporal central slowing.  This finding indicates etiologically nonspecific focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology, and is consistent with patient's history of right craniotomy.  Breach artifact indicates skull defect in that region.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indications for seizures persists, a repeat study with sleep may be of benefit.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 60-year-old male with hypertension, diabetes, and left ACA infarct, right-sided weakness, patient recently suffered 2 generalized tonic-clonic seizures with prolonged postictal state.  The patient is in Room 772.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not possible.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The overall EEG is quite slow, with a mixture of theta and delta.  Superimposed upon this are bursts of sharply contoured slowing and occasional sharp waves or sharply contoured delta maximum at T1 or T3.  As the recording continues, the patient starts to wake up a bit spontaneously with the appearance of alpha frequency activity in the background, right greater than left, and a posterior dominant rhythm of 8 Hz on the right, a bit disrupted on the left.  When unstimulated the patient starts to transition into a sleep pattern but overall, as the recording continues, the overall background is improving and the patient starts to transition to more of a stage 1, stage 2 sleep pattern.
At the end of the record, the patient is talking, there is an increase in alpha and theta frequency activity, although the patient is confused.
Heart rate 116 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal but dynamic record due to:
Bilateral, significant background slowing noted early in the record which improved over time.
Left temporal focal slowing or left hemispheric focal slowing.
Sharp waves seen at T3 and T1.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the fifth EEG for this patient.  It is better organized at the end of record than previous studies.  No seizures were recorded.  And the epileptiform activity and the background slowing are significantly less prominent than in some previous studies.  The best fit for this EEG is a postictal pattern in a patient who is improving.

EEG LENGTH:  23 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 57-year-old woman with a history of recent left MCA distribution ischemic stroke, who is scheduled to undergo left CEA tomorrow on 01/03/2013.
MEDICATIONS:  Nystatin, Lovenox, and Protonix.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to a standard 10-20 system with a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed. Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is a significant right-to-left interhemispheric asymmetry with slower wave forms at higher amplitudes over the left hemisphere.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the right hemisphere reaches 9 to 9.5 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  Additionally, there is an anterior-to-posterior frequency MCA gradient observed over the right hemisphere.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the left hemisphere is very unstable and reaches maximum about 8 Hz and it does not appear to attenuate with eyes opening.  There is no AP gradient over the left hemisphere.  Additionally, there is continuous polymorphic theta and delta observed over the left hemisphere.  Occasionally brief bursts of diffuse frontally predominant rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA) is captured.  This activity is higher in amplitude over the left hemisphere.  During drowsiness bursts of theta and delta activity seen over the right hemisphere and frequency of FIRDA increases.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation does not result in additional abnormalities.
FINDINGS:
Continuous moderate left hemispheric slowing.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and drowsy 23-minute EEG due to continuous moderate left hemispheric slowing.  This finding indicates a focal left hemispheric dysfunction, likely structural in etiology, and in this patient is consistent with a history of recent left MCA territory infarct.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Left-sided weakness.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This patient is a 57-year-old female with left-sided facial weakness, left facial droop, lupus, hypertension, discoid lupus, alcohol abuse, and history of intracranial bleed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
MEDICATIONS:  Cyclobenzaprine, Ambien, diltiazem, levothyroxine, and hydroxychloroquine.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens up with posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There was some frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation which produced no abnormal discharges.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and stage I sleep.
Heart rate:  72 with some PACs.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow wave seen almost continuously over the left hemisphere at T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.  At times there is loss of faster frequencies noted over that region.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal electroencephalogram due to left midtemporal focal slowing and loss of faster frequencies.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural cerebral dysfunction, which is consistent with a known hemorrhage in that region.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 59-year-old woman with a skull defect due to surgical intervention for a possible AVM who presents for a follow up EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Neurontin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is relative to eye opening.  There are some frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures, specifically hyperventilation accentuates the focal slowing which I will describe in the abnormal discharges.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and stage I sleep.
Heart rate 72.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
A single focal sharp wave was seen at T4 during the recording while asleep.
Continuous focal slowing seen at F7, T3 throughout the recording at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
Focal slowing seen intermittently at F8, T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  None.
Please note that the focal slowing in the left anterior temporal region at times has a sharply contoured morphology, but it is not clearly epileptic.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to single right mid temporal sharp waves in addition to continuous focal slow waves in the left anterior temporal region with some intermittent focal slowing in the right anterior temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures possibly arising from the right mid temporal region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal structural dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region which is consistent with the known surgery and injury.
Lastly, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right anterior temporal region which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures were clearly seen.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  23 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 43-year-old woman with a past medical history of seizures.  She has not had any seizures recently.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol and Trileptal.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consisted of a well formed and modulated moderate amplitude 9.5 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During drowsiness, the posterior dominant rhythm attenuates but stage II sleep is not achieved.  Intermittent bursts of theta and delta activity are captured over the bitemporal regions.  Activity within these bursts is often sharply contoured; however, no clear sharp waves are observed within these bursts of slowing.  Additionally, there is significant EMG artifact during some parts of the recording and epileptic activity could have been missed as a result of this.
FINDINGS:
No sleep.
Intermittent moderate bitemporal slowing, often sharply contoured.
No clear epileptiform discharges; however, portions of the recording contain significant EMG artifact and epileptiform discharges could have been missed.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and drowsy EEG due to moderate bitemporal slowing that is often sharply contoured.  This finding indicates underlying cerebral dysfunction, possibly structural in etiology.  No clear epileptiform discharges were captured; however, portions of the recording contain significant EMG artifact and epileptiform discharges could have been missed.  If clinical indication for seizures persists, a repeat study with stage II sleep and less artifact could be of benefit.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  26 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 59-year-old gentleman with a history of schizophrenia who presents with altered mental status and at least 2 episodes of tonic posturing with decreased responsiveness in the setting of ingesting Vicks VapoRub.
MEDICATIONS:  Lovenox, Ativan 1 mg at 6:00 a.m. and several mgs on 01/13/2013.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode with a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  There is right-to-left interhemispheric asymmetry with slower wave forms observed over the left hemisphere.  The background consists of a mixture of diffuse beta, theta, and delta activity.  Additional polymorphic often sharply contoured delta is observed over the left hemisphere, primarily over the left temporal region.  Several electrographic seizures are captured in this recording.  Seizures have abrupt onset without clear localization or lateralization.  Electrographically diffuse EMG artifact is observed.  Once the EMG artifact resolves generalized sharply contoured approximately 3 Hz rhythmic delta activity is observed diffusely, but it is higher in amplitude over the left hemisphere.  This activity increases in amplitude and decreases in frequency to approximately 2 Hz and often evolves into another episode of generalized EMG artifact that obscures the recording.  Once that EMG artifact resolves, rhythmic sharply contoured 3-4 Hz delta activity is often observed over the left temple region.
Clinically it appears that the patient moans and slobbers at the onset of seizure and has decreased responsiveness during the seizure.
FINDINGS:
Focal status epilepticus.
Excess beta.
Left hemispheric slowing most pronounced over the left temporal region.
Mild to moderate diffuse slowing.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 26-minute electroencephalogram due to diffuse slowing, focal left hemispheric slowing that is most pronounced over the left temporal region and multiple focal left temporal electrographic seizures without returning back to baseline.  Diffuse background slowing indicates etiologically nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  Focal left hemispheric slowing that is most pronounced over the temporal region indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, and in this case, could partially be to related post-ictal phenomenon.  Multiple electrographic and clinical seizures captured during the recording are consistent with focal status epilepticus.  These findings were conveyed to the Neurology consult team at the time of the recording.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 64-year-old male who made a suicide attempt with baclofen ingestion, brought to the hospital on 01/18/2013 and coded, now with myoclonic jerks.
MEDICATIONS:  Dopamine, vasopressin, norepinephrine.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient was intubated and comatose. No jerking was noted.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a burst suppression or discontinuous pattern.  The overall pattern when the record is suppressed is essentially a completely flat and suppressed pattern.  The bursts of activity may include isolated discharges or pairs of discharges which achieve approximately 200 mV.  Tactile stimulation of the patient and auditory stimulation of the patient do not activate the record.  The duration of the periods of suppression are on the order of 20 seconds.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior temporal focal slowing as well as simple partial seizures arising from the central region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal simple partial seizures arising from the central region, which are consistent with the known lesions in that region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region, which is also consistent with the lesions. This report was dictated and communicated to the team.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Right-sided weakness.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 53-year-old man with increased left-sided weakness, also right MCA stroke.
MEDICATIONS:  None mentioned.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with the addition of anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta in the left hemisphere and some decreased attenuated amplitude over the right hemisphere.
Photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.  Patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Right hemisphere attenuation and focal slowing is seen intermittently at F4.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  66.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to right hemisphere attenuation of faster frequency and focal slowing in the right frontal region
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral cortical dysfunction in the right hemisphere, maximal in the frontal region, which is consistent with an old stroke. No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 62-year-old with diabetes and epilepsy after aneurysm repair.  Seizure on February 23, with loss of consciousness, numbness of the hands and slurring speech and hyperactive eye movements.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Tylenol with codeine.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Patient was relatively somnolent. Photic stimulation was completed. Hyperventilation was deferred.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat disorganized, but there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  Occasional bursts of shifting slowing are noted in wakefulness and into drowsiness.  Broadly contoured vertex sharp waves were noted.  EKG artifact was a bit more prominent on the left, but there was also a very slight suggestion of a bit more focal slowing on the left compared to the right.
Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.
Heart rate 96 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
Occasional burst of shifting slowing.
A very subtly symmetry with a bit more sharply contoured slowing in the left frontotemporal frontocentral region relative to the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No definitive sharp waves were noted, although this EEG was remarkable for a fair amount of both EKG and eye movement artifact.  Additional EEG recording with more extensive sleep may be helpful to characterize epileptiform activity.  In this individual with a history of previous aneurysm, no cranial defect was noted by the tech and there was no definitive breech rhythm.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 75-year-old woman admitted with acute and chronic subdural hematoma status post surgery 04/04/13 with left frontal skull defect.  History of dementia, psychosis, autism, depression, hypothyroidism.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Klonopin, Gabapentin, Seroquel, and many others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed at bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient is in a hard collar and isolation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates an asymmetry.  The activity from the right hemisphere includes a mixture of data with smaller amounts of delta in this awake patient.  There is abundant 6 Hz activity and a glimpse of an 8 Hz alpha rhythm. The activity is relatively attenuated on the left.  As the patient becomes drowsy, the right hemisphere transitions a bit more towards the delta pattern.  There is some sharp wave contoured theta noted in the right hemisphere, particularly at T2 and there was also some arrhythmic delta activity in the right posterior quadrant as the patient becomes drowsy.
Heart rate 96 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal electroencephalogram due to:
Intra-hemispheric asymmetry with relative attenuation of the activity on the left compared to the right.
Background slowing noted bilaterally, right greater than left.
There are some subtle sharp waves noted on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a structural or functional abnormality on the left and the attenuated pattern is relatively characteristic of a subdural hematoma.  The sharp waves noted are relatively subtle.  These findings should be correlated with imaging.  Overall, this electroencephalogram supports a bihemispheric process, impacting the left hemisphere more so than the right but a subdural hematoma can attenuate the EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 58-year-old right-handed gentleman, who presents with seizures.  It is described as a generalized tonic-clonic seizure.
PAST MEDICAL HISTORY:  Significant for seizure disorders, hypertension, hyperlipidemia, schizophrenia, ethanol abuse, head trauma.  Head CT showed right MCA stroke.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Serax, vancomycin, lisinopril, thiamine, folic acid, Norvasc.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 9 Hz seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is generalized low amplitude beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  There are almost continuous right frontotemporal slowing at times with loss of faster frequencies.  There is occasional independent left temporal slowing, most pronounced in mid and anterior temporal region lasting for 1 or 2 seconds with a frequency of 2 to 2.5 Hz.  Drowsiness was is characterized by disappearance of the posterior dominant rhythm and slowing of the background and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact.  Heart rate was 80 to 90 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to,
Right hemispheric slowing with loss of faster frequencies.
Left temporal slowing.
There is no epileptiform activity or seizures noted during this recording.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Continuous right hemispheric slowing is consistent with an underlying structural abnormality, in this case right MCA stroke.  Left temporal slowing is consistent with left temporal dysfunction.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  Generalized beta activity could be due to medication effect including benzodiazepine or barbiturate, and also could be due to anxiety or hyperthyroidism.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were seen in this record.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or of intermittent seizures.  If seizures are a clinical concern, a repeat sleep-deprived EEG or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 47-year-old male with epilepsy and seizure related subdural hematoma in 2010, last seizure 2 months ago.  The patient amnestic for the seizure.  Now with right leg and hip weakness requiring a cane.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm, but there is a small amount of 7 Hz theta activity identified in the background.  Hyperventilation is performed early in the record increasing the amplitude of the background and producing a small amount of theta.  Features of drowsiness include attenuation of the alpha rhythm, and increase in theta and slow rolling eye movements.  Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
Photic stimulation was remarkable for photo electric artifact.
Heart rate 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This a mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Mild excess theta noted in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this EEG or in the previous EEG.  If epilepsy is an important consideration a follow-up test which may be a sleep-deprived EEG or a more prolonged sleep EEG may be helpful in capturing epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 61-year-old right-handed lady presenting with left arm and face numbness and weakness of 1 day duration.  She was found to have a subcortical CVA on CT scan of the head.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, acetaminophen, heparin, labetalol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement and one channel of EKG.  Wakefulness and sleep were captured.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a posterior dominant rhythm of 9-10 Hz frequency which is symmetric on both sides and reactive to eye opening.  There is a good anterior and posterior gradient.  There is some shifting slowing as the patient drifts into sleep.  Stage 2 sleep was achieved which was characterized by vertex waves, K complexes and spindles.  There was a wicket rhythm noted in stage 2 sleep.  As the recording progresses there are F7 sharp waves and rare T1 sharp waves which were identified as not being a part of the wicket rhythm.
Photic stimulation was performed which elicited a spiky driving response.
There was excessive theta in early drowsiness and right focal slowing as she became drowsy.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Excessive theta in early drowsiness.
Right focal slowing during drowsiness.
F7, T1 sharp waves in stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The left anterior temporal sharp waves are suggestive of a possible underlying epileptogenic process in the left anterior temporal region.  Clinical correlation is recommended.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status, probable seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This 52-year-old lady presents with change in mental status.  She had a seizure in the ED with left upper extremity shaking, right eye twitching, unresponsiveness.
PAST MEDICAL HISTORY:  Diabetes, hypertension, asthma, dementia, dyslipidemia, depression, right thalamic stroke, ambulatory dysfunction, hirsutism.
MEDICATIONS:  Heparin, aspirin, Lipitor, metoprolol, insulin, Protonix.
INTRODUCTION:  The digital video EEG was performed in the lab using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement and one channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.
TECHNICAL PROBLEMS:  There was a problem with the EKG leads throughout the study.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness the background is diffusely slow in the theta and delta range.  No posterior dominant rhythm was appreciated.
No clear distinction between sleep and wakefulness could be made on the EEG.
Photic stimulation was performed which did not bring about a change in the record.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Bifrontal slowing in the delta range was noted almost continuously.  The slowing was more prominent in the F3 and F4 regions.
There were rare F4 sharp waves seen.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Bifrontal F3 and F4 continuous focal slowing.
Rare F4 sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures arising from the right frontal region.  The bifrontal slowing indicates a possible underlying structural abnormality in these areas.  Clinical correlation recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This 52-year-old woman presents with confusion followed by a seizure in the emergency room with left arm shaking and right eye twitching.  This was followed by unresponsiveness and generalized weakness.  History of asthma, depression, dementia, and thalamic stroke.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, Keppra, Protonix, aspirin, and metoprolol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel EKG.  The patient was relatively somnolent.
TECHNICAL ISSUES:  T1 and T2 impedances were 5.7 and 5.9.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In relaxed wakefulness, there was more of a theta frequency background.  There was a subtle asymmetry with rare sharply contoured transients in the hemisphere.  As the patient transitions to sleep, POSTS were noted.  The overall background is a bit more symmetric and there is more of a slow pattern.  Snore artifact was observed.
Heart rate:  BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Shifting asymmetries.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In comparison to a previous study performed on the 24th, the background is overall significantly improved.  There are no major epileptiform discharges and no seizures were recorded.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  23 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 51-year-old woman with a history of right MCA stroke and bipolar disorder as well as seizure disorder.  She now presents with being found unresponsive on the floor.  She has approximately 1 seizure a month.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  The recording was performed at bedside.  Some of the electrodes had high impedances due to poor patient cooperation throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is a right to left interhemispheric asymmetry with faster frequencies observed over the left hemisphere.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the left hemisphere consists of polymorphic moderate amplitude 8.5 to 9 Hz alpha activity.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the right hemisphere consists of polymorphic low to moderate amplitude 7 to 8 Hz theta.  The anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient is weak bilaterally.  No normal sleep architecture is captured.  Additional diffuse polymorphic theta is observed.  Intermittent left hemispheric sharp waves are captured.  Phase reversal occurs over F7, T1, T3 and Fp1, F3 electrodes.  There is nearly continuous EMG artifact that effects variable leads.  Premature QRS complexes are captured on a single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
Mild diffuse slowing.
Mild to moderate right hemispheric slowing.
Intermittent sharp waves over the left frontal/anterior temporal region.
Occasional premature QRS complexes seen on EKG.
EMG artifact that is nearly continuous effecting variable leads throughout the recording.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake only 23 minute EEG due to mild diffuse slowing, mild to moderate right hemispheric slowing, as well as intermittent left frontal/anterior temporal epileptiform discharges.  Diffuse slowing indicates etiologically nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  Focal right hemispheric slowing indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology, and is consistent with the patient's history of right MCA territory stroke.  There is an epileptogenic focus over the left frontal/anterior temporal region.  A large amount of EMG artifact is present throughout the recording, so subtle abnormalities might have been missed.  No clear electrographic seizures are captured.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 43-year-old man who presents with a history of syncope with associated chest pain.  Prior to the event the patient felt lightheaded and dizzy.  There was positive loss of consciousness and shaking.
CURRENT MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, oxycodone, Dilaudid, lorazepam, Protonix, Xanax, and Lovenox.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation was  performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated moderate amplitude 10.5 Hz activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  The anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient is present, but weak.  Diffuse excess beta activity is present throughout the recording.  During drowsiness the posterior dominant rhythm attenuates.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving multiple flash frequencies.  A paced cardiac rhythm is noted on a single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
Mild disorganization.
Excess beta.
No epileptiform discharges.
No stage 2 sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal awake and drowsy 22 minute EEG due to mild background disorganization.  This findings indicates etiologically nonspecific cerebral dysfunction.  The excess beta could be secondary to medication effect such as benzodiazepines and barbiturates.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not preclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 56-year-old woman with right MCA CVA, status tPA.  She is now postoperative day #1 after craniotomy.  Worsening edema, mass effect, shift.  Possible seizure on the morning of 05/23/2013.
MEDICATIONS:  Clonidine, tramadol, Depakote.  Propofol drip stopped 1-2 hours prior to the EEG.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient was responsive during the EEG.  Prominent craniotomy changes were noted.  This is a somewhat technically challenging bedside ICU record.  The patient also had tender scalp and ideal impedances could not be obtained.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates an asymmetry between the 2 hemispheres.  The left hemisphere is medium amplitude with primarily 6 Hz theta and smaller amounts of delta.  The right hemisphere is a lower voltage, slower more featureless pattern, with a little bit of theta noted at the midline at CZ.  The patient is confused, but responsive at times and then drifts off to sleep with a slower pattern and a bit more delta on the left compared to the right.  The patient does seem to transition into more of a sleep state on the left intermittently with what may be somewhat asymmetric vertex waves, but deeper stages of sleep were not sustained.
Heart rate:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Marked slowing on the right.
Moderate slowing on the left, but with a definable drowsy and sleep pattern on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  This EEG supports a bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function effect.  The continuous focal slowing from the right with disturbance of faster frequency on the right is congruent with the right hemispheric infarct with mass effect and edema.  The slowing on the left may be due to the mass effect in shift or may be due to other diffuse disturbances.  No epileptiform features were identified.  These findings may be correlated with imaging as a fluid collection can attenuate EEG activity on the right.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  An 80-year-old woman with intracerebral hemorrhage, right PCA CVA, prior left-sided CVA.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, metformin, Zocor, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was very uncomfortable and had difficulty tolerating the electrodes.  Impedances were more challenging as the result.
TECHNICAL:  Impedance issues, patient cooperation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This bedside EEG demonstrates an asymmetry.  The right hemisphere is composed primarily of arrhythmic delta as well as some theta and smaller amounts of beta.  The left hemisphere on occasion includes some 7 Hz activity.  There is sharply-contoured slowing, some periodic slowing and even some sharp waves noted in the left hemisphere with variable maximum but more typically occipital or posterotemporal in nature.  On occasion, there is an alerting with a glimpse of an alpha rhythm on the left.
Heart rate 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Intrahemispheric asymmetry with marked slowing on the right and disruption of faster-frequency activity.
Irregular slowing on the left with periodic slowing and occasional sharp waves in the left posterotemporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures were recorded.  The markedly slow pattern on the right with disruption of faster-frequency activity and arrhythmic delta activity is supportive of a process in the right involving gray and white matter.  The left
hemisphere is also slow and disorganized, with some sharp waves.  These findings may be correlated with a previous stroke on the left.  No seizures were identified.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 44-year-old male with refractory epilepsy, presented to the emergency room after seizure at home, had another seizure in the emergency room and then a complex partial seizure in front of the resident at 8:00 p.m.  The patient remains poorly responsive.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Protonix, Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was quite somnolent during the EEG and had a seizure.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing began, the background EEG was quite slow and disorganized.
Interictal epileptiform discharges were identified with low amplitude sharp waves seen primarily in the right temporal region.
A seizure was identified shortly after the start of the EEG around 2:06 a.m. lasting approximately 1 minute.  This was characterized by eye flutter.  The patient was on the video and it is a bit hazy but the technologist described eye flutter and the video also seems to generate an arousal.  The first seizure out of the right is about 1 minute long and as the epileptiform activity evolves and slows a second seizure lasting approximately 20 seconds is noted out of the left.  This is associated with much higher amplitude slow delta and it ends abruptly.  During the left temporal seizure the patient has repetitive jerking of the trunk that occurred during the second seizure.  The first seizure was at 2:19.
Low amplitude intermittent left temporal sharp waves were noted to follow this.
No additional seizures were noted on the baseline EEG.
Heart rate 102 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Marked background slowing.
A right temporal lobe seizure.
A second seizure which localizes to the left and seems to evolve just as the seizure out of the right ends.
Marked background slowing.
Heart rate reaching 150 bpm during the second seizure out of the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is diagnostic of the localization related epilepsy.  The clinical history with onset of seizures before 8 a.m., failure to awaken and the presence of this seizure on the EEG raises concerns about a later form of status epilepticus.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  26 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 61-year-old man with history of seizures. Seizures are described as episodes of blurry vision, dizziness and inability to communicate lasting approximately 2-3 minutes.  The last generalized tonic-clonic convulsion was several years ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed using standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode and single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of low to moderate amplitude 10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eye opening.  There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies of lower amplitude anteriorly.  Diffuse beta activity is captured.  During sleep symmetrical vertex waves and sleep spindles noted.  Intermittent polymorphic, often sharply contoured, theta and delta activity is captured over the left temporal region.  Hyperventilation is performed with fair effort and produces no significant change in the background.  Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetric occipital driving at medium to high flash frequencies.  No clear electrographic discharges are captured.
FINDINGS:
Intermittent mild to moderate focal left temporal slowing, often sharply contoured.
Excess beta.
No clear epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and asleep 26 minute EEG due to intermittent mild to moderate focal left temporal slowing.  This finding indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, possibly structural in etiology.  Excess beta could be secondary to the medication effect such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  The lack of epileptiform discharges noted on a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 44-year-old male with refractory epilepsy, admitted to the unit with repetitive seizures.  He had 2 tonic-clonic seizures and was admitted for persistent postictal obtundation.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was somnolent and uncooperative.  Impedances were challenging.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is diffusely slow, but with generous beta activity, particularly in the central regions.  Stimulation of the patient produces muscle, a brief alerting, and some theta as well as transient alpha activity, but then the patient drifts back to sleep.
Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Excessive beta.
Generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  This EEG is most compatible with postictal state and/or medication effect.  No epileptiform features were identified.  The background EEG is similar to a previous postictal EEG recorded a month ago, but low voltage temporal spikes were not identified today, and no complex portal seizures were recorded.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Episodes of pressure and electric shocks in the head.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 59-year-old woman with a history of meningioma resection in 2009, has had episodes of vertigo, headaches since December and with left-sided head pressure, electric shocks that make her shake every 1-2 days, increasing lately.  She also states that thunder has a negative effect on her.
MEDICATIONS:  Amitriptyline, metoprolol, aspirin, pravastatin, omeprazole, clonazepam.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches at 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is excessive frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation produced abnormal discharges.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness, stage 1 and stage 2 sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen almost continuously at T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.  In addition, there is an asymmetrical increased amplitude and faster frequencies in this region consistent with a breach rhythm.  Please note that at times, there are sharply contoured discharges, but not clearly epileptiform.
Heart rate 78.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left midtemporal focal slowing and breach.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left midtemporal region, which is consistent with a known tumor resection surgery.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.  Please note that this is reported similar to the EEGs done in 2011, 2010 and 2009.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 40-year-old man with past medical history of seizures and cerebellar atrophy and cerebral palsy.  Patient had a seizure a week prior to the EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Depakote, ranitidine.
INTRODUCTION:  This is digital video EEG performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This is a diffusely slow EEG with a glimpse of 7.5 Hz alpha rhythm.  There was subtle right delta rhythmic activity.  As the patient gets drowsy, there is underlying right temporal TIRDA activity and sharply contoured slowing in T2.  There is generous beta activity on vertex waves in a stage I of sleep.  Hyperventilation causes focal slowing on the right temporal region, and photic stimulation induces driving response at 11 Hz.
Heart rate is 72.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to,
Focal slowing on the right temporal region.
Excessive beta activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are no epileptiform features on this EEG.  There is excessive beta activity that could be due to medications.  The left focal slowing can be seen in temporal lobe epilepsy and structural abnormality of the left temporal lobe.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 25-year-old male status post a brain tumor resection in childhood, status epilepticus March 23, 2013 associated with cerebritis/stroke.  This is an awake and drowsy record in a cooperative patient.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Vimpat.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG demonstrates an asymmetry between the 2 hemispheres.  The right hemisphere includes an 8 Hz alpha rhythm.  The left hemisphere demonstrates some underlying focal slowing in the left posterior temporal region with a breach rhythm, accentuation of amplitude in that region, some underlying delta.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background slowing.
In the context of a breach rhythm, there is an underlying, P3/T5 sharp waves, primarily noted at P3.
Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record.  Hyperventilation produces some bilateral slowing.  Frontally predominant rhythmic theta was noted in hyperventilation.
Heart rate 78 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing noted from both hemispheres, the left more so than the right.
Subtle underlying delta noted in the left hemisphere, particularly in the posterior quadrant.
Breach rhythm.
Subtle underlying left parietal sharp waves in the context of a breech rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  For this individual with a structural lesion and previous status epilepticus, this EEG is improved compared to other studies.  The patient is clearly awake with a well-formed alpha rhythm on the right, although it is a bit slow.  The focal features described above are compatible with the patient's known structural abnormality.  No seizures were recorded.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 31-year-old male status post gunshot wound to the head with left encephalomalacia, parietal injury.  Previous seizures in 2011, when the patient stopped his medications.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with on channel EKG.  Previous craniotomy defect was noted.  This was a technically satisfactory record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively low-voltage.  A 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm was identified bilaterally but it is somewhat higher amplitude on the left compared to the right.  The left hemisphere demonstrates a breech rhythm with accentuation of amplitude in that region and some head rocking artifact in the left centrotemporal region.  Hyperventilation was performed early in the record, producing an increase in amplitude and accentuating the difference between the two hemispheres.  This finding was also noted in drowsiness.  As the patient drifts in and out of sleep, there are bursts of paroxysmal rhythmic slowing, which are a little higher amplitude with accentuation of fast activity, again on the left compared to the right.  As the patient transitions into stage 2 sleep, spindle activity is noted.  The patient remains drifting in and out between stage 1 and stage 2 sleep during photic stimulation.  The tech attempt awaken the patient for photic stimulation but he keeps drifting back into stage 2 sleep.  Photic stimulation does not otherwise activate the record.
Heart rate 60 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal electroencephalogram due to:
Subtle focal slowing from the left hemisphere.
Despite the prominent breach rhythm, in the transition to sleep, there does appear to be an F7, FP1 sharp wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In comparison to previous EEG, 05/12/2011, the overall background has improved.  The focal slowing on the left is not as prominent and has more of a centrotemporal localization.  Sharp waves today were noted, more from the left frontal region and were previously in the left temporal region.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  Nearly 21 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 58-year-old man with a complicated past medical history who presented with status epilepticus.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  There is no clear posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The voltages are diffusely very low.  The background consists of a mixture of low voltage fast activity in the beta frequency range mixed with frequent periods of background discontinuity.  No normal sleep architecture is present.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  There is reactivity to visual auditory tactile and noxious stimulation characterized by   overall improvement in the background discontinuity.
FINDINGS:
A frequent period of discontinuity.
Diffuse beta.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 21 minute comatose EEG due to nearly continuous low-voltage beta activity and frequent periods of discontinuity.  These findings indicate etiologically nonspecific moderate to severe diffuse cerebral dysfunction that could partially be related to a medication effect.  Beta could be secondary to a medication effect such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  No electrographic seizures were captured.  These findings were conveyed to the Primary Team.

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.

The background consists of a mixture of low voltage fast activity in the beta frequency range mixed with frequent periods of background discontinuity.  No normal sleep architecture is present. A frequent period of discontinuity.
Diffuse beta.

Beta could be secondary to a medication effect such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  No electrographic seizures were captured.  These findings were conveyed to the Primary Team.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 25-year-old man, with history of left parietal mass resection and radiation therapy, presents with seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Vimpat, Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while drowsy.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 7 Hz, seen best over the right hemisphere.  There is a lack of normal frontal central beta over mainly over the left hemisphere, but also attenuated on the right.  Activating procedures were not performed.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.
Abnormal discharges:
Continuous polymorphic delta seen at 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts at T3 in the entire left hemisphere, maximal at T3-T5, and at times more anteriorly.  At times, they become monomorphic and there appear rhythmic but not clearly epileptiform.
Generalized slowing at 5-7 Hz seen continuously throughout the recording.
Heart rate:  84.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior hemisphere polymorphic slowing, maximal at F3-T5, in addition to some more anterior slowing.  Lastly, there is also mild to moderate generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with focal cerebral dysfunction seen in the left hemisphere, maximal in the posterior quadrant, but also involving the most anterior temporal region which is, in part, related to then known tumor resection, but the additional more anteriorly slowing may be nonspecific in regards to etiology.  Lastly, there is evidence of mild to moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures were seen.
