CLINICAL HISTORY:  Patient is a 25-year-old man with a history of left parieto-occipital tumor removal at the age of 12 with subsequent localization-related epilepsy, who now presents with worsening right-sided weakness and aphasia.
MEDICATIONS:  Current medications include Vimpat, Depakote, and Versed administered at approximately 8:54 a.m. on 08/14/2013.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1-T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  The recording was reviewed intermittently by the attending neurologist.  The patient was equipped with the event button.  Medical staff notes and nursing staff notes were reviewed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is a right-to-left interhemispheric asymmetry with faster waveforms at lower amplitudes over the right hemisphere.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the right consists of polymorphic 8 Hz to 9.5 Hz activity with weak anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient and additional polymorphic theta and delta activity more pronounced anteriorly.  There is no posterior dominant rhythm over the left hemisphere, and there is no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient over the left hemisphere.  The background over the left hemisphere consists of a mixture of polymorphic theta and delta activity at higher amplitudes.  Additional underlying faster activity is observed over the left.  Normal sleep architecture including sleep spindles, slow-wave sleep, vertex waves are captured.  Sleep architecture is more pronounced over the left.  A prolonged seizure starts at approximately 7:55 a.m. on 08/14/2013.  Seizure ultimately ends at approximately 8:55 a.m. on 08/14/2013, after 2 mg of IV Versed.  Seizure starts with low-to-moderate amplitude, somewhat rhythmic sharp waves observed over the left occipital region.  This activity gradually spreads to contralateral occipital region.  As seizure evolves, sharp waves with after going slow waves increase in amplitude and decrease in frequency.  Seizure spreads throughout the left hemisphere.  Eventually, a reflection of this activity is observed over the right hemisphere.  Clinically, horizontal nystagmus is noted.  Once 2 mg of Ativan are administered at approximately 08:54:40 a.m., seizure stops approximately 15 seconds later.   Please note there is diffuse excess beta activity observed throughout the recording.
FINDINGS:
Mild diffuse slowing.
Moderate focal left hemispheric slowing.
Left hemispheric breach artifact most pronounced over the left parasagittal leads.
A prolonged, approximately 1-hour, focal left hemispheric seizure that starts over the left occipital region.
Seizure stops approximately 15 seconds after administration of Versed.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 24-hour continuous video EEG monitoring, due to:
Mild diffuse slowing, focal moderate left hemispheric slowing, and focal left hemispheric status epilepticus that starts over the left occipital region.  Mild diffuse slowing indicates etiologically nonspecific, mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction.
Focal left hemispheric slowing indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology, and in this patient at least partially related to the postictal slowing.
Focal left occipital status epilepticus lasting approximately 1 hour and stopping after 2 mg of Versed.
These findings were conveyed to the neurology primary team at the time of the review.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  Patient is a 25-year-old man with a history of a left parieto-occipital tumor removal who now presents with worsening right-sided weakness and a change in mental status.
MEDICATIONS:  Vimpat 100 mg twice per day, Depakote 500 mg twice per day, Klonopin 1 mg twice per day, and phenobarbital 60 mg twice per day.
INTRODUCTION:  Condition of the recording:  The recording is performed according to the standard 10-20 system with the addition of T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead. The recording was performed continuously with audio/video capabilities.  Patient was provided with the event button.  Medical staff notes and nursing staff notes were reviewed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  There is right to left interhemispheric asymmetry with slower waveforms at high amplitudes over the left hemisphere.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the right hemisphere consists of moderate amplitude, well-formed and modulated 9 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly over the right hemisphere.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the left hemisphere is unstable, which is 8-9 Hz alpha activity.  There is no anterior to  posterior frequency amplitude gradient over the left hemisphere.  The background over the left consists primarily of a mixture of polymorphic theta and delta activity, with the delta activity most pronounced over the left anterior temporal/frontal region.  Normal sleep architecture including sleep spindles, vertex waves, and slow wave sleep is observed.  The patient spent a lot of time in sleep.  No electrographic seizures are captured.
FINDINGS:
Focal left hemispheric slowing, most pronounced over the anterior temporal/frontal region.
No electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  This is abnormal 24-hour continuous audio/ video EEG monitoring due to continuous moderate left hemispheric slowing most pronounced anteriorly.  This finding indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology, and in this patient is partially related to postictal phenomenon.  No electrographic seizures were observed.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 69-year-old woman with complex partial epilepsy.  She presents for a “follow-up” EEG.  Seizures are characterized by dizzy spells, most recent seizure 1 week ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Phenytoin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is a technically satisfactory EEG, although impedances in the T1-T2 electrodes were not ideal.  There was a fair amount of muscle and chew artifact noted in the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG demonstrates a small amount of disorganization with a low voltage, 10 Hz alpha rhythm and generous beta.  There is also some background theta noted.  Prominent theta frequency activity is noted in the temporal regions as the patient transitions in and out of sleep.  This is irregular, sharply contoured, and resembled wicket aside from its irregularity.  No definitive sharp waves are noted in these discharges, however.  Other features of drowsiness include an increase in beta and overall background slowing as well as attenuation of the alpha rhythm.
Hyperventilation did not significantly activate the record.  Photic stimulation was performed as the patient was drifting in and out of sleep and scant driving was noted.
Heart rate 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
A mild degree of background disorganization for an adult of this age in wakefulness.
Sharply contoured theta noted in drowsiness, which resembles wicket but is somewhat irregular and somewhat more prominent on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No definitive sharp waves or spikes were noted.  The paroxysmal discharges described above are outside of the range of normal for a benign variant but do not have the characteristic shape of an epileptiform discharge.  Despite this, they still may represent an inter-ictal discharge for this individual.  Additional EEG recording capturing deeper stages of sleep may be of use.  Alternatively, comparison with previous studies may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 25-year-old man with a history of a left parieto-occipital tumor removed at the age of 12, who now presents with recurrent left occipital seizures.  The patient subsequently found to have a small left occipital bleed.
MEDICATIONS:  Vimpat, Depakote and phenobarbital and 2 mg of Ativan this a.m.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed continuously.  Spike detector and seizure detector were activated.  Medical staff notes and nursing staff notes were reviewed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The background consists of a mixture of low amplitude beta activity admixed with theta and delta.  Delta activity is more pronounced anteriorly especially over the left hemisphere.  Additional polymorphic delta is noted over the left hemisphere.  No normal sleep architecture is observed, but periods of quiescence are noted.  On 08/23/2013 between approximately 6:50 a.m. until approximately 7:59 a.m., approximately 8 electrographic seizures were observed.  They last from about 1 minute to 2-1/2 minutes.  One more seizure is observed after Ativan administration.  The seizures started with very low amplitude fast activity over the left occipital region that rapidly spread throughout the left hemisphere, decrease in frequency and increasing in amplitude.  As the seizure progresses, frequency of rhythmic activity decreases to approximately 3 Hz and gradually stops.  Clinically seizures are associated with rhythmic lateral gaze nystagmus to the right.
FINDINGS:
Moderate diffuse background slowing.
Focal left hemispheric slowing.
Excess beta.
Multiple electrographic seizures between approximately 7:00 a.m. and 8 a.m. on 08/23/2013 that is improved with Ativan.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 24-hour continuous audio/video EEG monitoring due to moderate diffuse slowing, focal left hemispheric slowing, and multiple focal electrographic seizures that occur within 1 hour at the end of the recording epoch.  Diffuse slowing indicates etiologically nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction, that is in this case likely related to medication effect.  Focal left hemispheric slowing indicates focal cerebral dysfunction likely structural in etiology and at least partially related to postictal phenomenon.  Excessive beta could be secondary to medication effect such as benzodiazepines __________  There is an epileptogenic focus over the left occipital region and is consistent with a history of recent left occipital region bleed.  These findings were conveyed to the Neurology primary team.
